TRAILER RUPTURE DISC BLEW OUT WHEN DRIVER PUT AIR PRESSURE ON THE TRAILER TO UNLOAD. NO PRODUCT WAS SPILLED. THE DRIVER THEN TRIED TO TAKE THE TRAILER BACK TO THE TERMINAL FOR REPAIR INSTEAD OF CALLING FOR REPLACEMENT RUPTURE DISC. WHEN HE PULLED OUT ONTO ST. RT. 7 PRODUCT SPLASHED OUT OF THE OPEN RUPTURE DISC HOLE ONTO THE ROADWAY. THE SPILL WAS CLEANED UP BY BAYER CORP. EMERGENCY RESPONSE UNIT AND THE MARTINS FERRY FIRE DEPARTMENT. THE TRAILER WAS SECURED AND RETURNED TO ITS TERMINAL.

CARRIERS UNIT WAS PRESENTED FOR UNLOADING. WHEN DRIVER PRESSURIZED TRAILER FOR UNLOADING A SLIGHT LEAK FROM THE FLANGE ON TOP OF THE TRAILER WAS OBSERVED. CARRIERS DRIVER IMMEDIATY SHUTDOWN AIR SUPPLY AND DEPRESSURIZED TRAILER TO ALLOW FOR INVESTIGATION OF SOURCE AND CAUSE OF LEAK. DRIVER AND UNLADING PERSONNEL FOUND GASKET IN PRESSURE VALVE TO BE DEFECTIVE. CARRIER SENT PERSONNEL TO CUSTOMER'S PLANT AND CHANGED GASKET AND TRAILER WAS RETURNED TO THE ORIGINAL SHIPPER FOR DISPOSITION. PRODUCT THAT WAS SPILLED APPROXIMATELY 5-10 GALLONS WAS CONTAINED IN CONTAINMENT AREA BY RECEIVER AND NEUTRALIZED AND DISPOSED OF.

DURING THE UNLOADING PHASE OF TRAILER, COMPANY ASSOCIATE WAS ATTEMPTING TO MOVE DRUM WITH DRUM TRUCK AND PUNCTURE BOTTOM EDGE CAUSING MINIMAL SPILLAGE OF PRODUCT. SPILLAGE WAS MITIGATED AND CONFINED TO AREA OF DRUM ON TRAILER FLOOR.

ACFX 18762 NOTED WITH PRODUCT ODOR IN AREA OF CAR BY CARRIER PERSONNEL. THE CAR WAS ISOLATED AND THE SHIPPER NOTIFIED.  SHIPPER REPRESENTATIVES RESPONDED AND FOUND THE SAMPLE LINE VALVE PLUG LOOSE ALLOWING A SLIGHT VAPOR RELEASE.  THE PLUG WOULD NOT PROPERLY TIGHTEN SO A NEW PLUG WAS INSTALLED STOPPING THE RELEASE.

PRELIMINARY REPORT IS THAT THE DRIVER OF THE PICKUP TRUCK WAS SPEEDING AND INTOXICATED.

A DUMP TRAILER LOAD OF WASTE MATERIAL (LARGELY DEBRIS IN NATURE:WOOD, PAPER, SAND/SOIL, PPE ETC) CONTAMINATED WITH RCRA CHARACTERISTIC METALS & ORGANICS (SEE MANIFEST FOR SPECIFIC LIST) CLASSED AS A HAZARDOUS WASTE SOLID CAUGHT FIRE WHILE SITTING IN THE TRANSIT YARD TWO DAYS AFTER BEING LOADED.  MATERIAL WAS IN YARD ENTIRE TIME.  THE SPECIFIC CAUSE OF THE FIRE IS UNDETERMINED BUT IS NOT BELIEVED TO BE EQUIPMENT RELATED.  FIRE WAS NOTICED SUNDAY 7/1/01 AT 6:30 AM BY SECURITY GUARD WHO CALLED THE FIRE DEPARTMENT AND COMPANY PERSONNEL.  FIRE DEPARTMENT EXTINGUISHED FIRE WITH RESULTING FIREWATER RUNOFF ENTERING CITY STORMWATER SEWER, SOLID MATERIAL WAS CONTAINED WITHIN THE DUMP TRAILER.  MATERIAL REMAINING AFTER FIRE WAS REMOVED FROM THE DUMP TRAILER, CONTAINED (PLASTIC/BOOMS ETC.) ON SITE (PAVED AREA) BY COMPANY EMERGENCY RESPONSE PERSONNEL.  MATERIAL AND CONTAINMENT ITEMS WERE LOADED INTO ANOTHER DUMP TRAILER FOR SHIPMENT TO ORIGINAL HAZARDOUS WASTE FACILITY.  THE DUMP TRAILER BODY WAS BASICALLY DESTROYED AND THERE WAS NO OTHER PHYSICAL OR PROPERTY DAMAGE.  TWO POLICE OFFICERS WERE SENT FOR OBSERVATION/CHECKUP AS PRECAUTIONARY MEASURES ONLY WITH NO RAMIFICATIONS.

THE OVERPACK DRUM WILL BE FORWARDED ON TO THE CONSIGNEE ALONG WITH THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED.  WHILE UNLOADING, TWO LEAKING, ONE HUNDRED AND TWENTY GALLON POLY TOTES WERE DISCOVERED IN THE REAR OF THE TRAILER.  APPROXIMATELY ONE QUART OF FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED.  THE TOTES WERE LEAKING DUE TO LOOSE BUNGS.  THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING LEVEL C PROTECTION, AMPHOMAG, ABSORBENT PADS, AND WATER.  THE CLEANUP MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO TWO, TWENTY-FIVE GALLON POLY RECOVERY DRUMS WHICH WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION.  THE LOOSE BUNGS WERE TIGHTENED AND THE TOTES WERE CLEANED OFF AND FORWARDED ON TO THE CONSIGNEE ALONG WITH THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: CARGO TANK WAS LOADED WITH 10,500 GALLONS OF JET FUEL, ENTERING THE THRUWAY EASTBOUND AT EXIT 38.  FOR REASONS YET UNKNOWN, THE UNIT DRIFTED OVER THE EDGE LINE OF THE RAMP.  APPARENTLY, THE DRIVER OVERCORRECTED AND THE UNIT ROLLED OVER.  WEATHER, CONDITIONS NOT FACTORS.

DRIVER NOTICED FOG COMING OUT OF TRAILER AND PULLED OFF THE SIDE OF THE ROAD.  DRIVER REPORTED LIQUID DRIPPING OUT OF TRAILER.  EMERGENCY RESPONSE COMPANY WAS CALLED AND DISPATCHER OHIO STATE PATROL WAS ALSO CALLED. EMERGENCY RESPONSE COMPANY CONTAINED LEAKING DRUM AND CLEANED UP SPILL. THE DRUM APPEARED TO FAIL AT THE SEAM.

column58: Auxiliary Valve; Bottom Outlet Valve; Piping or Fittings
column168: THE WASTE CORROSIVE LIQUID WAS PUMPED INTO THE CARGO TANK ON MONDAY 7-2-01. THE TANKER LEFT IMMEDIATELY FOR THE DESTINATION FACILITY.  THE DRIVER HAD TRAVELED APPROXIMATELY 70 MILES WHEN A PASSING MOTORIST INDICATED THAT THE CARGO TANK WAS LEAKING.  THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY EXITED INTERSTATE 94 SOUTHBOUND AT THE LAKE FOREST, IL OASIS AND STOPPED HALFWAY UP THE EXIT RAMP TO INSPECT THE CARGO TANK.  THE INSPECTION VERIFIED THAT THE TANKER WAS LEAKING AT THE BOTTOM/CENTER VALVE.  THE DRIVER MOVED THE TANKER TO THE FAR WEST PORTION OF THE OASIS PARKING LOT AND ENGAGED THE VACUUM ON THE CARGO TANK.  THE VACUUM TEMPORARILY STOPPED THE LEAK.  APPROXIMATELY 10 MINUTES AFTER THE VACUUM WAS STARTED THE CARGO TANK BEGAN VENTING A VAPOR CLOUD.  THE ILLINOIS STATE POLICE AND LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENTS WERE NOTIFIED AND ARRIVED AT THE SCENE AT 9:49 AM.  AT APPROXIMATELY 10:00 AM THE DECISION WAS MADE TO EVACUATE THE OASIS AND 48 HOMES IN A HALF MILE RADIUS WEST OF THE INCIDENT.  THE ACID CORRODED THE REMAINDER OF THE VALVES AND THE ENTIRE CONTENTS OF THE CARGO TANK WERE RELEASED AT APPROXIMATELY 11:00 AM.  AT 12:45 PM INDIVIDUALS WERE ALLOWED TO RETURN TO THEIR HOMES.  AT 3:00 PM THE OASIS WAS REOPENED.  THE SPILLED ACID DRAINED NORTH APPROXIMATELY 1000 FEET ON THE CONCRETE PARKING LOT THEN ENTERED A STORM DRAIN AND TRAVELED APPROXIMATELY 600 FEET IN A DRAINAGE DITCH.  ALL LIQUIDS WERE COLLECTED, THE PARKING LOT WAS NEUTRALIZED/CLEANED, AND 17 ROLL-OFF BOXES OF SOIL WERE EXCAVATED ONYX IS INVESTIGATING THE COMPATIBILITY OF THE WASTE WITH THE TANKER AND PREVIOUS CONTENTS, ALONG WITH THE CONSTITUENTS IN THE WASTE IN AN ATTEMPT TO DETERMINE THE CAUSE OF THE INCIDENT.

column168: ON JULY 4, 2001, IN THE CSXT YARD IN SELKIRK, NY, CSXT PERSONNEL NOTICED GATX 97601 LEAKING VAPORS FROM THE TOP.  THE CAR WAS ISOLATED AND A CSXT SUPERVISOR FOUND A LOOSE PLUG (LESS THAN TOOL TIGHT) ON THE A-END LIQUID VALVE.  THE PLUG WAS TIGHTENED AND THE LEAK STOPPED.  THE CAR WAS MONITORED PERIODICALLY FOR 24 HOURS BY A CSXT HAZMAT CONTRACTOR AND NO FURTHER LEAKAGE WAS NOTED.  THE CAR WAS RELEASED FOR SHIPMENT.  NARRI = 5(5+5+0)(2+0) =100  CODE = 312

column168: ECUX 461220 WAS FOUND LEAKING WHILE IN TRAIN MOVEMENT WITHIN CSX TRANSPORTATION'S RAIL YARD AT NEW ORLEANS, LA.  THIS CAR LOST APROX. 1/2 GALLON OF LIQUID FROM THE MANWAY AREA OF THE CAR DUE TO IMPROPER TIGHTENING OF THE MANWAY COVER BOLTS. column168: PICKED UP SHIPMENT AT A CUSTOMERS OF NJV'S IN DAYTONA BEACH, FL. 2 DRUMS WERE SHRINKED WRAPPED ON TO A PALLET, WHEN DRS OPEN HIS TRAILER AT THE NEXT CUSTOMER, HE DISCOVER THAT THE DRUMS HAD FALLEN OFF THE PALLET WITH THE SHRINK STILL INTACT, BUT 1 OF THE DRUMS HAD BEEN DAMAGED AND HAD A CUT IN THE BOTTOM OF IT.

THE SHIPMENT IN QUESTION WAS LOADED AND NOT PROPERLY PROTECTED FROM OTHER FREIGHT.  A SKID WAS LOADED NEAR THE DRUM.  THE SKID, DURING TRANSIT, RUBBED A HOLE IN THE SIDE OF THE DRUM.  A LIQUID WAS NOTICED LEAKING WHILE THE DRIVER WAS DOING HIS PRE-TRIP.  THE SET WAS BROKEN DOWN AND WE OPENED THE TRAILER.  WE THEN  NOTICE THE EXACT DAMAGE AND THE CAUSE.

column62: Defective Component or Device; Water Damage
column168: ON JULY 9, 2001 A 55 GALLON DRUM WAS RECEIVED AT CLEAN HARBORS ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES, INC'S. (CHESI) 10 DAY TRUCK TO TRUCK TRANSFER FACILITY, LOCATED AT 2930 INDEPENDENCE ROAD, CLEVELAND, OHIO 44115. THE DRUM WAS NOT LEAKING AT THAT TIME, BUT IT APPEARED TO HAVE A POTENTIAL ISSUE. THE DRUM WAS PLACED INSIDE A CONTAINMENT UNIT MADE OF PLASTIC WHICH WAS ATTACHED TO A METAL BRACE SECURED WITH METAL BOLTS. WHILE SITTING IN IT THE CONTAINMENT UNIT THE DRUM RUPTURED CAUSING MATERIAL TO LEAK AND REACT WITH THE METAL BOLTS CAUSING THE MATERIALS TO ESCAPE THE UNIT. APPROXIMATELY 5 GALLONS OF HAZARDOUS WASTE WAS RELEASED. THE MATERIAL INSIDE THE DRUM WAS WASTE CORROSIVE LIQUID, ACIDIC INORGANIC, N.O.S. (NITRIC ACID, HYDROCHLORIC ACID) 8, UN3264, PG II. THE MATERIAL WAS IMMEDIATELY CONTAINED AND CLEANED UP BY CHESI PERSONNEL.
WHILE UNLOADING, EMPLOYEE OVERFILLED TANK CAUSING APPROXIMATELY 5 GALLONS OF PRODUCT TO BE LOST. CLEANUP PERFORMED BY INDUSTRIAL MARINE SERVICES WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT.

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL

column168: DRIVER WAS ATTEMPTING TO VENT TANK WHEN PRODUCT BEGAN TO SPRAY CAUSING APPROXIMATELY 5 GALLONS OF PRODUCT TO BE LOST. CLEANUP PERFORMED BY ACT AND EMPLOYEE WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT.
DRIVER UNLOADED AND KNEW HE HAD TOO MUCH PRODUCT BUT FAILED TO SHUT DOWN IN TIME AND TANK OVERFLOWED. USED SPILL PADS FOR CLEAN UP.
SHIPPER LOADED 5000 POUNDS IN OUR TRAILER & PRODUCT STARTED TO DRIP OUT OF BOLTS ON BELLY OF THE TRAILER. WILL OFF LOAD AND PUT IN ANOTHER TRAILER.
TANK NOT VENTED AT END OF UNLOAD PRODUCT WAS SPRAYING OUT OF CONNECTOR BETWEEN FILL LINE & TANK= RIGHT AT THE POINT WHERE PIPE GOES INTO TANK
DRIVER LOADING TRAILER CUSTOMER AUTHORIZED = CHANGING PRODUCTS IN THE COMPARTMENT WANTED TO PUT 2900 GALLONS IN COMPARTMENT 3 AND IT ONLY HOLDS 2500 GALLONS.  TRAILER WAS OVER LOADED SHIPPER
DRIVER CLEARING LINES AND PRODUCT FOAMED OUT.  CUSTOMER HOSED DOWN INTO DRAIN.
UNLOADER SAID PLENTY OF ROOM 1/2 INTO UNLOAD PRODUCT CAME OUT VENT ON TOP TANK.  DRIVER SHUT DOWN SITE GAUGE IS WRONG.  METER NOT WORKING PROPERLY
DRIVER FINISHED UNLOADING WALKING HOSE AND DIDN'T HAVE IT HIGH ENOUGH AND SPILLED PRODUCT USED SPILL PADS TO CLEAN UP

THE DRIVER OPENED THE INTERNAL VALVE TO ALLOW PRODUCT TO FLOW INTO THE DISCHARGE LINE SO THAT THE EXTERNAL VALVE COULD THEN BE OPENED AND THE CUSTOMER COULD PULL THEIR SAMPLE.  BEFORE THE EXTERNAL VALVE WAS OPENED, THE HYDRAULIC RELEASE HANDLE WAS RELEASED TO CLOSE THE INTERNAL VALVE TO PREVENT ANYMORE PRODUCT FROM ENTERING THE DISCHARGE LINE.  DUE TO THE PLUNGER FAILING TO FALL BACK INTO PLACE, THE VALVE DID NOT SEAL, THEREFORE ALLOWING PRODUCT TO CONTINUE TO FLOW.  THIS, IN TURN, CAUSED THE SPILL.

column168: LOOSE CAP ON TOTE.  LIQUID SLOSHED OUT IN TRANSIT TO CONSIGNEE.  APPROX 5 GALLONS SPILLED IN TRL.  CONTAINED RECAPPED & RECOOPED.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Inadequate Blocking and Bracing
column168: THE SHIPMENT WAS LOADED ON THREE PALLETS IN A TRIANGLE SHAPE IN THE NOSE OF THE TRAILER.  THE FIRST PALLET WAS NOT PROPERLY BLOCKED TO PREVENT SHIFTING.  THE PALLET SHIFTED TO THE RIGHT DURING TRANSIT AND THE DRUMS WERE DISPLACED FROM THE PALLET AND DISPENSED ABOUT THREE POUNDS OF UPON HITTING THE TRAILER FLOOR.  THE TOPS WERE RESECURED TO THE DRUMS AND THE SHIPMENT WAS FORWARDED TO DESTINATION.

column168: FOUR OF EIGHT MANWAY COVER SECUREMENT BOLTS LOOSE, UTLX 801547, JULY 10, 2001, DETROIT DIVISION.  AT APPROXIMATELY 0930 HOURS, TUESDAY, JULY 10, 2001, AT LIVERNOIS YARD IN DETROIT, MICHIGAN, FRA INSPECTOR GARY THOMPSON NOTED AN ODOR EMANATING FROM TANK CAR UTLX 801547, CONTAINING SULFUR, MOLTEN.  APPROPRIATE NOTIFICATION MADE. THOMPSON EXAMINED THE TANK CAR AND DETERMINED THERE WERE FOUR OF EIGHT MANWAY COVER SECUREMENT BOLTS LOOSE. EXCESSIVE PRESSURE ON EMPTY CAR, PTRX 7017, JULY 09, 2001, SOUTH JERSEY DIVISION. AT APPROXIMATELY 0800 HOURS, MONDAY JULY 09, 2001, AT STONEY CREEK YARD N TRAINER, PA , TANK CAR PTRX 7017, CONTAINING ETHYLENE REFRIGERATED LIQUID WAS NOTED VENTING. APPROPRIATE NOTIFICATION MADE. A REPRESENTATIVE OF SUNOCO AND REPRESENTATIVES OF UNION TANK CAR ARRIVED AT THE SITE, EXAMINED THE TANK CAR AND DETERMINED THERE WAS EXCESSIVE PRESSURE ON EMPTY TANK CAR. THEY PRESSURE TESTED THE TANK CAR AND DETERMINED IT SHOULD BE PLACE IN SUN IMMEDIATELY. AT APPROXIMATELY 1000 HOURS, THE TRAIN CREW YPSC02 PLACED THE TANK CAR. NARRI=5(4+5+0)X(2+0)=90

column168: BNSF SWITCH CREW REPORTED TANK CAR LEAKING VAPOR.  BNSF RESPONDERS FOUND THE SRV (SAFETY/PRESSURE RELIEF VALVE) BASE BOLTS LOOSE AS THEY WERE TOO LONG & BOLTS REPLACED WITH 4 SHORTER ONES & TOOL TIGHTENED.  FILL HOLE COVER GASKET PINCHED & WAS REALIGNED.  THE TWO SWITCH CREW MEMBERS FINDING LEAK WERE TAKEN TO HOSPITAL FOR EXAM FOR CHEMICAL INHALATION EXPOSURE, TESTED & RELEASED WITH NO LOST WORK DAYS.

CHLORINE ODOR REPORTED IN YARD & SUSPECT TANK CAR ISOLATED.  OCCIDENTAL CHEMICAL CHLOREP TEAM TIGHTENED TWO LOOSE MAIN PLATE (PRESSURE PLATE) SECUREMENT BOLTS, ELIMINATING ODOR & VAPOR RELEASE.  TANK CAR FORWARDED TO AUTHORIZED REPAIR FACILITY IN MARSHALL, TX

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Inadequate Blocking and Bracing
column168: TRAILER REPORTED LEAKING & TAKEN TO CONTAINMENT AREA.  CONTRACT REPONDER FOUND BANDED DRUMS ON PALLET THAT HAD BROKEN AWAY FROM THE SMALL BANDING & RUBBED AGAINST ONE ANOTHER IN TRANSIT RESULTING IN WEAR HOLES IN FOUR DRUMS.  CONTRACTOR CLEANED SPILLED PRODUCT.  DAMAGED DRUMS OVERPACKED & FORWARDED TO SHIPPER BY CONTRACTOR.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Inadequate Blocking and Bracing; Too Much Weight on Package
column168: TRAILER REPORTED LEAKING & TAKEN TO CONTAINMENT AREA.  SHIPPER CONTRACTOR FOUND ONE METAL PAIL HAD BEEN PARTIALLY CRUSHED BY HEAVY LADING PLACED ATOP & HAD RUBBED AGAINST A PIECE OF PARTICLE BOARD ON THE PALLET NEXT TO THIS PAIL RESULTING IN A WEAR HOLE.  DAMAGED PAIL OVERPACKED & SPILLED PRODUCT REMEDIATED BY CONTRACTOR.

column168: NSRR SWITCH CREW REPORTED CAR LEAKING FROM BOTTOM OUTLET INSIDE SHIPPERS FACILITY.  SHIPPER RESPONDERS CLOSED/TIGHTENED TOBOV(TOBOV(TOP OPERATED BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE) & REPLACED ONE OF TWO MISSING BOLTS AT THE BASE OF BOTTOM OUTLET ASSEMBLY.  THE OTHER BOLT WOULD NOT THREAD INTO HOLE & ASSUMED PREVIOUS BOLT HAD BROKEN OFF INSIDE THREADED HOLE.  LEAKAGE CEASED AFTER SECUREMENT COMPLETED.  SPILLED PRODUCT WAS CAPTURED IN CONTAINMENT PAN WITH LESS THAN 1/2 GALLON ONTO GROUND.

CONTRACTOR CLEANED SPILLED PRODUCT & PLACED IT IN A CONTAINMENT DRUM FOR DISPOSAL;  ADJUSTED LOAD & PLUGGED PLASTIC TOTE TO PREVENT FURTHER LEAKAGE.

column168: ALASKA RR CARMAN INSPECTING CARS IN BARGE STAGING YARD, DISCOVERED FRESH PRODUCT ON SIDES OF TANK CAR.  SHIPPER CONTRACT RESPONDERS FOUND THE MANWAY COVER BOLTS TIGHT BUT THE MANWAY COVER GASKET WAS MISSING ALLOWING PRODUCT TO SLOSH OUT.  RESPONDERS INSTALLED NEW GASKET & WIPED SPILLED PRODUCT FROM TANK CAR SIDES.  AFTER CAR WAS DECONTAMINATED IT WAS RELEASED TO PROCEED TO DESTINATION.

column168: BNSF TRAIN CREW REPORT TANK CAR LEAKING FROM BOTTOM OUTLET & TRAIN WITH CAR TAKEN TO GUEMSEY (APPROX). 8 MILES) WERE BNSF RESPONDERS TIGHTENED(CLOSED) THE TOP OPERATED BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE (TOBOV) 1 1/2 TUMS.  AFTER TOBOV CLOSED, THE SMALL LEAK FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET FLANGE AREA CEASED.  PRODUCT WAS UNLOADED AT GUEMSEY.  SPILLED PRODUCT TRICKLED ALONG THE RIGHT OF WAY, NOT CONCENTRATED IN ANY ONE LOCATION.

column58: Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug); Manway or Dome Cover; Piping or Fittings
column168: WHILE LOADING A TOTE ONTO OUR TRAILER, THE FORKLIFT DRIVER TURNED AND WHEN HE TURNED THE TOTE TIPPED OVER, THE TOTE IS TALL AND TOP HEAVY, AND LANDED ON A YELLOW CONCRETE POLL.  WHEN THE TOTE HIT THE POLL THE PRESSURE POPPED THE LID OFF AND LIQUID SPRAYED ON THE FLOOR.  THE DRIVER OF THE FORKLIFT, IN A PANIC, MOVED THE LIFT OUT FROM UNDER THE TOTE AND WHEN HE DID THE TOTE FELL ALL THE WAY OVER.  THE TOTE WAS QUICKLY PICKED UP AND EMPLOYEES WERE EVACUATED.  WE LOST APPROX.  350 GALLONS. NO INJURIES.  THE DOCK PLATE IS SLOPPED AND THE DRIVER  CAME IN AT AN ANGLE, CAUSING THE TO BE TO TIP. WE HAVE EXPLAINED TO THE DRIVER THAT HE NEEDS TO APPROACH THE TRUCK AND DOCK PLATE STRAIGHT AHEAD.

column42: PAINT RELATED MATERIAL INCLUDING PAINT THINNING, DRYING, REMOVING, OR REDUCING COMPOUND
column168: A 55-GALLON STEEL DRUM WAS IN TEMPORARY STORAGE AT THE TEN DAY TRANSFER FACILITY WHEN IT DEVELOPED A PINHOLE LEAK AND SPILLED TWO QUARTS OF PAINT RELATED MATERIAL INTO THE SECONDARY  CONTAINMENT AREA.  THE SPILL WAS IMMEDIATELY CLEANED UP WITH ABSORBENT MATERIAL AND THE LEAKING DRUM AND THE WASTE GENERATED WERE PLACED INTO A 85-GALLON SALVAGE DRUM. THE SPILL GENERATED APPROXIMATELY SEVEN POUNDS OF WASTE WHICH WAS TRANSPORTED ALONG WITH THE ORIGINAL WASTE, TO THE SAFETY-KLEEN FACILITY AT 3700 LAGRANGE ROAD FOR TREATMENT AND DISPOSAL.  THE DRIVER WHO PICKED UP THE WASTE DRUM WAS COUNSELED ON PROPER DRUM INSPECTION PROCEDURES TO ENSURE NO MORE FUTURE INCIDENTS.

column42: PAINT INCLUDING PAINT, LACQUER, ENAMEL, STAIN, SHELLAC SOLUTIONS, VARNISH, POLISH, LIQUID FILLER AND LIQUID LACQUER BASE
column168: A DRIVER ARRIVED AT HIS FACILITY AND WAS IN THE PROCESS OF UNLOADING HIS TRUCK WHEN HE DISCOVERED THAT A 55-GALLON STEEL DRUM CONTAINING PAINT RELATED MATERIAL WAS LEAKING.  APPROXIMATELY TEN GALLONS LEAKED INTO THE BACK OF THE TRUCK WHERE IT WAS CONTAINED AND WAS IMMEDIATELY CLEANED UP WITH ABSORBENT MATERIAL.  THE LEAKING DRUM AND THE WASTE GENERATED FROM THE SPILL WAS PLACED INTO AN 85-GALLON SALVAGE DRUM.  THE SPILL GENERATED APPROXIMATELY 150 POUNDS OF WASTE WHICH WAS TRANSPORTED, ALONG WITH THE ORIGINAL WASTE, TO THE SAFETY-KLEEN FACILITY AT 3700 LAGRANGE ROAD IN SMITHFIELD, KY FOR TREATMENT AND DISPOSAL.  THE DRIVER WAS COUNSELED ON PROPER DRUM INSPECTION PROCEDURES TO ENSURE NO MORE FUTURE INCIDENTS.

A DRIVER WAS AT A SAFETY-KLEEN FACILITY PUMPING OUT A WASTE SOLVENT STORAGE TANK INTO A TANKER TRUCK WHICH WAS THEN GOING TO A DISPOSAL FACILITY.  THE DRIVER HAD UNDERESTIMATED THE AMOUNT OF SOLVENT IN THE CARGO TANK AND SPILLED ONE GALLON OF MATERIAL ONTO THE CONCRETE SECONDARY CONTAINMENT AREA BEFORE HE COULD CLOSE THE SHUT OFF VALVE.  THE SPILLED MATERIAL WAS CLEANED UP WITH ABSORBENT PADS AND CONTAINERIZED.  THE SPILL GENERATED APPROXIMATELY FIFTEEN POUNDS OF WASTE WHICH WILL BE SENT TO THE SAFETY-KLEEN FACILITY AT 1200 SYLVAN STREET IN LINDEN, NJ FOR TREATMENT AND DISPOSAL.  THE DRIVER WAS COUNSELED ON PROPER TANKER LOADING PROCEDURES TO ENSURE NO MORE FUTURE INCIDENTS.
CYLINDER WAS KNOCKED OFF THE DOCK. DURING IMPACT THE IMPROPER CAP CAME OFF AND THE VALUE WAS CRACKED OPEN FROM IMPACT W/ THE PAVEMENT.
column172: Seamless cylinder made of definitely prescribed aluminum alloys

column58: Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug); Piping or Fittings
column168: TRAILER WAS LOADED BY OUR EMPLOYEE'S AT RUSSELLVILLE, SC.. LOADER FAILED TO CL0SE FRONT DONE LID OUR DRIVEN FAILED TO PERFORM PROPER PRE-TRIP. WHEN DRIVER MOVED TRAILER TO SCALE TO WEIGH PRODUCT. PRODUCT SPLASHED OUT OF OPEN DOME LID ONTO PAVEMENT

JACK B. KELLEY, INC. WAS TRANSPORTING A LOAD OF LIQUID HYDROGEN IN CARGO TANK #4694 WITH TRACTOR #5502. DELIVERY HAD BEEN MADE, THE VEHICLE HAD EXITED THE PLANT, AND THE DRIVER HAD SCALED HIS TRACTOR-TRAILER. HE THEN PROPERLY PARKED AND WENT INSIDE THE SECURITY BUILDING TO GET THE WEIGHT RECEIPT. WHILE THERE, A SAFETY DEVICE LIFTED FROM EXCESSIVE INTERNAL VESSEL PRESSURE. HYDROGEN VAPOR WAS IGNITED (WE BELIEVE) BY STATIC ELECTRICITY AND A HYDROGEN VENT STACK FIRE RESULTED.  PLANT EMERGENCY RESPONDERS, CARRIER SAFETY DEPARTMENTS, AND SHIPPER SAFETY DEPARTMENT WERE CONTACTED AND THIS INCIDENT WAS SAFETY RESOLVED. UPON INVESTIGATION, TRAILER WAS FOUND TO HAVE LOST IT'S VACUUM SURROUNDING THE INNER VESSEL., RESULTING IN AN INCREASE OF PRODUCT VAPOR PRESSURE. THE SAFETY DEVICE E FUNCTIONED PROPERLY AND NO SIGNIFICANT QUANTITY OF PRODUCT WAS DISPERSED. THERE WAS NO FAILURE OF THE CONTAINER, ONLY A LOSS OF VACUUM BETWEEN THE INNER VESSEL AND THE OUTER SHELL. THE CARGO TANK WAS EMPTY OF ALL LIQUID. THE REMAINING  PRODUCT WAS GAS VAPOR ONLY. THIS CARGO TANK WAS SAFELY REMOVED FROM THE INCIDENT SITE AND HAS BEEN TAKEN TO A QUALIFIED REPAIR FACILITY FOR FURTHER EVALUATION AND REPAIRS.

DOCK ASSOCIATE, GEORGE MAURIN, WAS UNLOADING THIS DRUM FROM A CITY PICK UP TRAILER.  HE WAS STAGING THE DRUM ON THE DOCK TO BE LOADED LATER IN THE SHIFT.  WHEN GEORGE ATTEMPTED TO PULL THE DRUM TRUCK OUT FROM UNDER THE DRUM, ONE CLEAT CAUGHT UNDER THE DRUM AND THE OTHER CAME OUT.  WHEN GEORGE ATTEMPTED TO EXTRACT THE 2ND CLEAT, THE DRUM TRUCK SPUN BACK INTO THE DRUM CAUSING THE FREE CLEAT TO PUNCTURE THE DRUM NEAR THE BOTTOM.  THE DRUM WAS IMMEDIATELY LAID ON ONE SIDE STOPPING THE LEAK.  EPOXY PUTTY WAS PLACED OVER PUNCTURE.  APPROX. 1 QUART OF MATERIAL ESCAPED.  THIS SPILL WAS CONTAINED WITH ABSORBENT SAND AND PUT  INTO A 5 GALLON PAIL AND SEALED. SPILL TOOK PLACE IN OPEN AIR DOCK AND WAS CONTAINED AND CLEANED UP IN LESS THAT 20 MINUTES.

WHILE LOADING THE CARGO TANK, THE EMPLOYEE HAD TWO STOCK TANKS OPEN WHILE PUMPING INTO CARGO TANK.  CARGO TANK OVERFILLED.  EXCESS WAS PUMPED BACK INTO THE STOCK TANKS.  SPILLAGE WAS BIOREMEDIATED PER THE KANSAS DEPARTMENT OF HEALTH AND ENVIRONMENT.

THE TANK CAR LEAKED DUE TO FAILURE OF RUBBER LINING IN THE CAR.  THE PRODUCT IN THE CAR CORRODED A SMALL HOLE IN THE STEEL SIDE OF THE CAR.  A HAZMAT TEAM WAS CALLED OUT WHEN THE LEAK WAS DISCOVERED.  THE HAZMAT TEAM CONTAINED THE SPILL, TRANSFERRED THE PRODUCT TO ANOTHER TANK CAR AND CLEANED UP THE CONTAMINATED RAIL BED.  AN FRA INSPECTOR CAME ON SITE AND WILL INVESTIGATE IF THE CAR WAS PROPERLY MAINTAINED AND INSPECTED BY THE CAR OWNER.

I WAS CALLED TO RESPOND TO A LEAKER IN UNLOAD DOOR 7 WEARING FULL PPE.  I FOUND A 5 PART HAZMAT WITH A STAINED SOAKED CORNER  CONSULTED DECISION TREE AND RESPONSE SHEET FOR CORROSIVE.  PACKAGE WAS CONTAINED IN SPILL TUB AND REMOVED TO HAZMAT RE- WRAP AREA  INSPECTION SHOW 1 OF 3 PLASTIC BOTTLES LEAKED DUE TO BEING CRUSHED.  PRODUCT WAS REPLACED IN SALVAGE DRUM AND RTS. WASTE WAS PROCESSED THROUGH DMP PROGRAM.

I WAS CALLED TO RESPOND TO A LEAKED IN UNLOAD DOORE 8 WEARING FULL P.P.E. I FOUND A 5 PART HAZMAT WITH STAINED IN ITS CORNERS CONSULTED THE DECISION TREE & RESPONSE SHEET FOR FLAMMABLE LIQUID PACKAGE WAS CONTAINED IN SPILL TUB & REMOVED TO HAZMAT REWRAP AREA INSPECTION SHOW 1 OF 1 PLASTIC JUGS LEAKED DUE TO LOOSE CAP.  PRODUCT WAS REPACKED IN SALVAGE DRUM & RTS WASTE WAS PROCESSED THROUGH DMP PROGRAM.
DRIVER/OPERATOR DID NOT HAVE TRAILER BELLY HOSE PROPERLY INSTALLED/SECURED. RE-TRAINED DRIVER.  CONTAMINATED SOIL HAS BEEN BIOREMEDIATED ON SITE.

PRO 245-705095 WAS PLACED ON DOCK WAITING TO BE LOADED. ANOTHER SKID FROM A DIFFERENT SHIPMENT WAS PLACED NEXT TO SKID OF PRO 245-705095. EITHER AT TIME SECOND SKID WAS PLACED NEXT TO SKID DAMAGED OR WAS PUSHED INTO SKID, THE SECOND SKID TORE THE BAG ON THE FIRST SKID ENOUGH TO ALLOW PRODUCT TO LEAK OUT. LEAKED PRODUCT PLACED IN RECOVERY DRUM. ALL SHIPMENTS SHOULD BE STAGED ON THE DOCK IN A MANNER THAT WILL PREVENT DAMAGE.
TOP OF DRUM LEAKING AT SEAM BASIC PACKAGE FAILURE

WHILE UNLOADING AN INBOUND TRAILER, DSR. JERRY NOONAN CAME TO ME WHEN HE NOTICED LIQUID ON THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER. WHILE I WATCHED, HE UNLOADED TWO MORE SKIDS TO FIND THE THIRD SKID FROM THE BACK WAS LEAKING. THE WOODEN SLATS ON THE SKID WERE NOT STRONG ENOUGH TO SUPPORT 1800 LBS OF 5 GALLON PAILS. ONE SLAT BROKE AND THE SPLINTERED END PUNCTURED ONE PAIL THE PAIL AND THE CLEAN UP MATERIAL WAS PUT IN A SALVAGE PAIL ON OUR DOCK.

column168: VOPAK DRIVER WAS MOVING FROM DELIVERY IN WILSONVILLE TO DELIVERY IN LAKE OSWEGO, MOTORCYCLE POLICEMAN FOLLOWED DRIVER FOR MORE THAN A MILE THEN PULLED VEHICLE OVER.  OFFICER INDICATED TO DRIVER HE SAW FUMES COMING FROM TRAILER AND SAID HIS EYES WERE BURNING.  DRIVER INSPECTED TRAILER AND SAW NO FUMES, NO SMELLS.  OFFICER INDICATED HAZMAT TEAM WAS DISPATCHED TO RESPOND AND MOVED DRIVER UPWIND.  FIRE ENGINE TEAM BLOCKED OFF AREA, AND INFORMED APARTMENT OCCUPANTS TO CLOSE WINDOWS BY POLICE.  OFFICER WAS RENDERED AID BY AMBULANCE AND TRANSPORTED TO A HOSPITAL.  HAZMAT TEAM SNIFFED AND ENTERED TRAILER - COULD NOT LOCATE ANY LEAKS BUT NOTED A POSSIBLE WET SPOT, AND A LIGHT CLOUD INSIDE.  HAZMAT FINISHED INSPECTION AND RELEASED TRAILER BACK TO DRIVER TO FINISH DELIVERIES. ALTHOUGH THERE APPEARS TO BE NO RELEASE OF PRODUCT, REPORT IS SUBMITTED FOR INFORMING DOT OF THE INCIDENT.

column168: WHILE EXITING FROM THE POLK COUNTY EXPRESSWAY ONTO THE AIRPORT ROAD EXIT RAMP, THE VEHICLE LEFT THE ROADWAY ON THE LEFT SIDE AND TRAVELED INTO THE GRASS SHOULDER. THE DRIVER ATTEMPTED TO BRING THE VEHICLE BACK ONTO THE ROAD. THE VEHICLE OVERTURNED AND CAME TO REST ON THE RIGHT SIDE. THE DRIVER WAS EJECTED FROM THE CAB DURING THE ROLLOVER. THE DRIVER DIED AS A RESULT OF BLUNT TRAMA TO THE HEAD. THE TRAILER LEAKED APPROX. 900-1000 GALLONS OF DIESEL FUEL UNTIL EMERGENCY RESPONSE PERSONNEL REMOVED THE REMAINING FUEL.

WEARING PROPER PPE I RESPONDED TO SPILL IN DOOR 8. I PUT HAZARDOUS PACKAGE IN GREEN BAG TUB. THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED IN AND ON THE PACKAGE. I NEUTRALIZED THE SODIUM HYDROXIDE SOLUTION WITH SODIUM BICARBONATE AND ABSORBANT. I THEN PUT THIS THROUGH THE DMP. THE ENTIRE GALLON WAS NEUTRALIZED. I USED THE DECISION TREE DURING THIS PROCESS. I THEN DECONTAMINATED ME AND MY PPE.

column168: ON 23 JULY 2001, DRIVER WILLIAM FULK WAS DISPATCHED IN TRACTOR 294 AND PULLING TRAILER 3730 WITH A LOAD OF SODIUM HYDROXIDE (AKA CAUSTIC SODA). LOADED IN CINCINNATI AND DELIVERED TO CHARTER STEEL IN RISINGSUN, OH. SOMETIME AFTER THE LOAD WAS DELIVERED, A CHARTER STEEL EMPLOYEE DISCOVERED THAT THEIR HOLDING TANK HAD OVERFLOWED THROUGH ITS VENT AND PRODUCT SPILLED ONTO THE GROUND THROUGH THE VENT PIPING.THERE WAS MINOR DAMAGE TO THE EXTERIOR OF THE BUILDING AND POSSIBLE DAMAGE TO TWO CARS THAT WERE PARKED BENEATH THE VENT PIPE. THERE WERE NO INJURIES ASSOCIATED WITH THIS INCIDENT. THERE IS NO ANTICIPATED ADVERSE AFFECT ON THE ENVIRONMENT RESULTING FROM THIS INCIDENT. SINCE THE PRODUCT WAS NOT CONTAINED A DOT 5800.1 MUST BE GENERATED. THE QUANTITY OF PRODUCT SPILLED IS BELIEVED TO BE 45-50 GALLONS (POSSIBLY LESS). THE RQ FOR SODIUM HYDROXIDE IS 78.125 GALLONS (AT 12.8 LBS. PER GALLONS). ON 27 JULY 2001, I RECEIVED A TELEPHONE CALL FROM TONY CHEVONY (CHARTER STEEL). MR. CHEVONY CALLED TO REPORT AN INCIDENT THAT HAD OCCURRED AT THE CHARTER STEEL FACILITY IN RISINGSUN, OH. MR. CHEVONY STATED THAT OUR DRIVER OVERFILLED THEIR HOLDING TANK AND PRODUCT SPILLED OUT (THROUGH THE VENT PIPING ONTO TWO CARS AND ALSO SPLATTERED ON THE EXTERIOR OF THE BUILDING. MR. CHEVONY BELIEVES THAT THIS INCIDENT WAS THE CAUSE OF THE DRIVER DOING SOMETHING WRONG AND FAILING TO REPORT THE SPILL THAT SHOULD HAVE BEEN OBVIOUS TO THE DRIVER. I INQUIRED AS TO HOW CHARTER STEEL DETERMINES THE CAPACITY LEVEL OF THE TANK. HE STATED THAT HE DID NOT KNOW HOW IT IS DETERMINED WHEN IT IS NECESSARY TO RE-SUPPLY THE PRODUCT. HE FURTHER STATED THAT THE TOTAL TANK CAPACITY WAS ABOUT 5,000 GALLONS. I WAS GIVEN PERMISSION TO VISIT THE FACILITY THAT AFTERNOON TO GATHER INFORMATION AND SEE THE DAMAGE. ACCORDING TO THE DRIVER, IT WAS ROUTINE DELIVERY AND THAT HE WAS UNAWARE OF ANY INCIDENT THAT HAD TAKEN PLACE. I SECURED THE WAYBILL FOR THIS LOAD AND OBSERVED THAT SOMEONE FROM CHARTER STEEL SIGNED THE CERTIFICATION BLOCK. THIS BLOCK STATES, " I CERTIFY THAT THE TANK TRUCK IS CONNECTED TO THE PROPER PIPING AND STORAGE TANK WHICH IS ASSIGNED TO RECEIVE THE NET WEIGHT OF THE COMMODITY NAMED ON THE BILL OF LADING". THE SHIPPING PAPER AND WAYBILL INDICATE THAT 3700 GALLONS OF PRODUCT WAS ORDERED. THE WEIGHT SLIP AGREES WITH THE AMOUNT ORDERED. I ARRIVED AT THE FACILITY AT ABOUT 1230 HOURS ON 27 JULY AS PLANNED. JIM STUCK (OPERATIONS SUPERVISOR) MET ME. THE FACILITY IS A MODERN STEEL PICKING PLANT AND APPEARS TO BE TWO OR THREE YEARS OLD. THE SITE HAS A DUEL PURPOSE LOADING/UNLOADING RACK FOR LOAD SPENT PHOSPHORIC ACID AND UNLOADING FRESH PHOSPHORIC ACID, HYDROCHLORIC ACID, AND CAUSTIC SODA. THE TRACTOR/TRAILER IS POSITIONED IN A DIKED CONTAINMENT AREA, WHILE LOADING /UNLOADING PRODUCT. THE CONTAINMENT SYSTEM IS EQUIPPED WITH A DRAIN., WHICH IS CONNECTED TO AN EFFLUENT SYSTEM. THERE ARE THREE MALE CAMLOCK FITTINGS AND ONE FOUR-BOLT FITTING MOUNTED ON THE EXTERIOR WALL. THESE FITTINGS ARE CLEARLY IDENT

column168: CARTON WAS CRUSHED BY OTHER FREIGHT, THE CARTON WAS OVERPACKED AND SENT TO DESTINATION.

ABOUT 3:45 AM EASTERN DAYLIGHT TIME, ON JULY 14, 2001, AT THE ATOFINA CHEMICALS, INC, (ATOFINA) PLANT IN RIVERVIEW, MICHIGAN, A PIPE ATTACHED TO A FITTING ON THE UNLOADING LINE OF A RAILROAD TANK CAR FRACTURED AND SEPARATED, CAUSING THE RELEASE OF METHYL MERCAPTAN, A POISONOUS AND FLAMMABLE GAS. ABOUT 4:09 AM, SHORTLY AFTER THE RIVERVIEW FIRE DEPARTMENT CHIEF ARRIVED ON SCENE, THE METHYL MERCAPTAN IGNITED, ENGULFING THE TANK CAR IN FLAMES AND SENDING A FIREBALL ABOUT 200 FEET INTO THE AIR. FIRE DAMAGE TO CARGO TRANSFER HOSES ON AN ADJACENT TANK CAR RESULTED IN THE RELEASE OF CHLORINE, A POISONOUS GAS THAT IS ALSO AN OXIDIZER. THE FIRE WAS EXTINGUISHED ABOUT 9:30 AM. THREE PLANT EMPOYEES WERE KILLED IN THE ACCIDENT. THERE WERE SEVERAL OTHER INJURIES; MOST OF THE INJURED WERE TREATED FOR RESPIRATORY SYMPTOMS AND RELEASED. ABOUT 2,000 RESIDENTS WERE EVACUATED FROM THEIR HOMES FOR ABOUT 10 HOURS. TWO TANK CARS, RAILROAD TRACK, AND PLANT EQUIPMENT (INCLUDING HOSES AND FITTINGS) WERE DAMAGED IN THE FIRE.

column168: THE DRIVER REPORTED DIFFICULTY ENTERING THE STATION PROPERTY DUE TO THE LARGE NUMBER OF PEOPLE PARTYING IN THE AREA IN CONJUNCTION WITH A LOCAL FESTIVAL.  AFTER THE DRIVER PARKED THE TRUCK, HE WENT INTO THE STATION TO OBTAIN A PRINT-OUT OF THE TANK INVENTORY.  WHEN HE RETURNED TO THE TRAILER, HE REMOVED THE FIRE EXTINGUISHER FROM THE VEHICLE, CONNECTED THE FITTINGS AND HOSES,  AND BEGAN TO UNLOAD.  WHEN HE OPENED THE TRAILER INTERNAL VALVES, PRODUCT FLOW WAS OBSERVED FROM A COMPARTMENT HE HAD NOT CONNECTED TO AN UNLOADING HOSE AND FITTING.  HE STOPPED UNLOADING IMMEDIATELY.  HE NOTIFIED STATION PERSONNEL, SOMEONE CALLED THE FIRE DEPARTMENT, AND THE STATION WAS CLOSED UNTIL THE EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR ARRIVE.  THE DRIVER STATED THAT WHEN HE LEFT THE LOADING TERMINAL ALL OF THE VALVES ON THE TRAILER WERE CLOSED.  WHEN HE ARRIVED AT THE STATION HE OBSERVED SEVERAL PEOPLE IN THE AREA THAT APPEARED TO BE INTOXICATED.  HE DID NOT OPEN ANY TRAILER VALVES UNTIL HE STARTED TO UNLOAD.

AS A RESULT OF THE COLLISION A FIRE STARTED.  DRIVER OF MOBIL TANKER MAINTAINED CONTROL OF TRUCK AND HE WAS ABLE TO STOP THE TRUCK IN THE PROPER PLACE(SIDE OF HIGHWAY). THEM THE DRIVER TRIED TO PUT THE FIRE OUT, HOWEVER, HE WAS NOT SUCCESSFUL. NO PRODUCT ESCAPED AND THE EMERGENCY VALVES WORKED.
WHILE UNLOADING, THREE BAGS WERE DISCOVERED TORN AND LEAKING. THE BAGS WERE RECOUPED INTO A CHEMICAL LINED, PROPERLY MARKED AND LABELED OVERPACK. THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED FOR DISPOSITION.

WHEN UNLOADING DRUMS FROM TRAILER WITH DRUM PICKER ATTACHMENT ON FORKLIFT, FORKLIFT OPERATOR LOWERED THE ATTACHMENT TOO HARD SUBSEQUENTLY PUNCTURING A HOLE IN THE DRUM AS A RESULT.  DRUM PATCH PUTTY WAS PLACED ON HOLE AND DRUM WAS PLACED INTO A RECOVERY CONTAINER AND RETURNED TO SHIPPER AS PER INSTRUCTED.  FORKLIFT OPERATOR WAS REVIEWED AND INSTRUCTED ONE THE PROPER AND SAFE USE OF DRUM PICKER ATTACHMENT.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Impact with Sharp or Protruding Object (e.g., nails)
column168: THIS PARTICULAR SHIPMENT WAS LOADED ON TO A DROPPED TRAILER BY SHIPPER. WHEN WE PICKED IT UP AND RETURNED TO OUR FACILITY THIS ONE DRUM WAS FOUND TO BE SLIGHTLY LEAKING FROM BOTTOM BECAUSE IT HAD BEEN PLACED ON TOP OF A PROTRUDING NAIL IN FLOOR.  DRUM WAS SEALED WITH PUTTY AND PLACED INTO A RECOVERY CONTAINER AND RETURNED TO SHIPPER AS PER INSTRUCTED.  SPILLED MATERIAL WAS CLEANED WITH ABSORBENT.

WHEN LOADING A PALLET OF MISCELLANEOUS FREIGHT INTO A TRAILER, FORKLIFT OPERATOR IMPROPERLY JUDGED HIS CLEARANCES AND STRUCK THE PALLET IN FRONT OF HIM WITH THE ONE HE WAS LOADING IN.  AS A RESULT, THE PALLET HE WAS LOADING PUNCTURED A BOX OF SAID MATERIAL AND RELEASED ITS CONTENTS.  ABSORBENT WAS USED TO CLEAN UP SPILLED MATERIAL AND WAS PLACED INTO A RECOVERY CONTAINER FOR FINAL DISPOSITION.  FORKLIFT OPERATOR WAS INSTRUCTED ON PAYING ATTENTION TO WHAT HE WAS DOING AND BE CONSTANTLY AWARE OF HIS SURROUNDINGS AND CLEARANCES.

DOCKWORKER WAS UNLOADING PALLET OF SAID MATERIAL THAT WAS STRETCH WRAPPED ON A PALLET WITH AN ELECTRIC PALLET JACK. WHEN THE BLADES OF THE JACK WENT THROUGH THE PALLET IT STRUCK AND RIPPED OPENED THREE BAGS THAT HAD FALLEN THROUGH THE BOTTOM OF THE PALLET UNDETECTED.  SPILLED MATERIAL WAS PLACED IN SALVAGE BAGS ALONG WITH SPILLED MATERIAL AND SHIPPED TO ULTIMATE CONSIGNEE.  THIS PROBABLY COULD HAVE BEEN PREVENTED IF ORIGINAL SHIPMENT HAD CARDBOARD PLACED ON THE PALLET TO PREVENT FREIGHT FROM FALLING THROUGH IT.

WHILE UNLOADING FREIGHT DOCKWORKER PLACED PALLET ON THE DOCK FLOOR RIGHT NEXT TO ANOTHER PALLET OF THE SAME ORDER.  WHEN HE PLACED IT DOWN HE WAS TOO CLOSE TO THE OTHER PALLET AND ONE DRUM HIT ANOTHER DRUM SLIGHTLY PUNCTURING THE BOTTOM CHIME.  DRUM WAS IMMEDIATELY LAID ON ITS SIDE AND DRUM PUTTY WAS PLACED ON THE HOLE AND THEN DRUM WAS PUT INTO RECOVERY DRUM AND RETURNED TO SHIPPER AS PER INSTRUCTED.

HE NEEDED TO MOVE IT UP JUST A "TAD" AND INSTEAD OF PICKING IT UP TO MOVE IT HE ELECTED TO PUSH THE PALLET WITH THE FORKBLADES.  WHEN HE DID THIS BOARD ON THE PALLET BROKE AND HIS BLADE HIT AND PUNCTURED ONE OF THE DRUMS ON THE PALLET.  DRUM WAS LAID ON ITS SIDE, REPAIR PUTTY APPLIED, AND PLACE INTO A RECOVERY DRUM AWAITING FINAL DISPOSITION.  FORKLIFT OPERATOR WAS REVIEWED WITH CORRECT AND PROPER HANDLING INSTRUCTIONS AND DISCIPLINED UNDER COMPANIES DISCIPLINARY GUIDELINES REGARDING SUCH MATTERS.

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED.WHILE UNLOADING, ONE CARTON CONTAINING NINE, ONE QUART PLASTIC JUGS FELL OVER IN THE REAR OF THE TRAILER. UPON FURTHER INVESTIGATION, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THREE PLASTIC JUGS WERE DAMAGED AND SIX WERE UNAFFECTED. APPROXIMATELY THREE QUARTS OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED. THE DAMAGE WAS DUE TO IMPROPER LOADING. THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING GLOVES, GOGGLES, TYVEK SUITS AND ABSORBENTS. THE CLEANUP MATERIALS, WET CARTON AND DAMAGED JUGS WERE PLACED INTO A FIVE GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM. THE RECOVERY DRUM WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION. THE SIX UNAFFECTED PLASTIC JUGS WERE REPACKAGED AND FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE ALONG WITH THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED. THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

THE CLEANUP MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO A FIVE GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM WHICH WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION. THE LOOSE BUNG ON THE LEAKING DRUM WAS TIGHTENED AND THE DRUM WILL BE FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE WITH THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED. THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

column168: A FORKLIFT DRIVER WAS AT A SAFETY-KLEEN FACILITY LOADING A TRAILER WHEN HE PUNCTURED A 55-GALLON STEEL DRUM WITH A FORKLIFT BLADE. THE MAJORITY OF THE MATERIAL WAS SPILLED ONTO THE BACK OF THE TRUCK; HOWEVER, SOME OF THE MATERIAL SPILLED ONTO THE ASPHALT LOADING AREA. THE SPILL WAS IMMEDIATELY CLEANED UP WITH ABSORBENT MATERIAL. THE LEAKING DRUM WAS PLACED INTO AN 85-GALLON OVERPACK AND THE WASTE MATERIAL WAS PLACED INTO A 55-GALLON STEEL DRUMS. THE SPILL GENERATED APPROXIMATELY 900 POUNDS OF WASTE WHICH WAS TRANSPORTED, ALONG WITH THE ORIGINAL WASTE, TO THE SAFETY-KLEEN FACILITY AT 1200 SYLVAN STREET IN LINDEN, NJ FOR TREATMENT AND DISPOSAL. THE FORKLIFT DRIVER WAS COUNSELED ON PROPER FORKLIFT OPERATING PROCEDURES TO ENSURE NO MORE FUTURE INCIDENTS.

column168: DRIVER WAS HEADING NORTH ON HWY 39/51 NORTH OF WOODRUFF. THE DRIVER SAW MOVEMENT NEAR THE CENTER OF ROAD. HE MOVED TO RIGHT TO AVOID A COLLISION WITH A WOMAN RUNNING ON THE ROAD. AT THAT TIME HE APPLIED HIS BRAKES. AT THE LAST INSTANT ANOTHER PERSON RAN ONTO THE ROADWAY GRABBING HER AND PUTTING HER DIRECTLY IN THE DRIVER'S PATH. HE SWERVED TO THE LEFT IN AN ATTEMPT TO AVOID HITTING THEM. BOTH PERSONS WERE STRUCK BY THE RIGHT FRONT FENDER AND BUMPER. THE FUEL SPLASHED UP FROM A COVER WHICH HAD NOT BEEN PROPERLY CLOSED.

column168: A DRIVER WAS AT A SAFETY-KLEEN FACILITY UNLOADING DRUMS OF WASTE SOLVENT OFF OF HIS TRUCK. THE SPILLED MATERIAL WAS IMMEDIATELY CLEANED UP WITH ABSORBENT ON THE TAILGATE AND A SMALL AMOUNT ON THE ASPHALT PARKING LOT. THE SPILL GENERATED APPROXIMATELY FIFTEEN POUNDS OF WASTE WHICH WILL BE TREATED AT THE SAFETY-KLEEN FACILITY AT 1142 GREEN HILL ROAD IN WEST CHESTER, PA  FOR DISPOSAL.  THE DRIVER WAS COUNSELED ON PROPER DRUM INSPECTION PROCEDURES TO ENSURE NO MORE FUTURE INCIDENTS.

column42: PAINT INCLUDING PAINT, LACQUER, ENAMEL, STAIN, SHELLAC SOLUTIONS, VARNISH, POLISH, LIQUID FILLER AND LIQUID LACQUER BASE
column168: OCCASIONALLY, A 55 GALLON DRUM OF PAINT IS TAKEN FROM SMI JOIST COMPANY TO SMI STEEL PRODUCT (APPROXIMATELY 3 MILES AWAY) TO PERFORM TOUCH-UP PAINTING AT A STORAGE YARD AT SMI STEEL PRODUCTS. ANY REMAINING PRODUCT IS RETURNED TO SMI JOIST. IN THIS CASE, APPROXIMATELY 5 GALLONS OF PAIN WAS USED. UPON LEAVING SMI STEEL PRODUCTS, THE DRIVER OF THE PICK-UP TRUCK LEFT THE PLAT AT A SPEED OF 5-10 M.P.H. WHILE MAKING THE TURN, THE BARREL TIPPED OVER, HITTING THE SIDE OF THE PICK-UP TRUCK. THIS CAUSED THE LID OF THE BARREL TO COME OFF CAUSING THE PAINT TO SPILL. THE STATE HIGHWAY POLICE AND THE HEMPSTEAD COUNTY SHERIFF'S OFFICE ASSISTED IN THE SPILL. A CREW OF SMI JOIST EMPLOYEES CLEANED UP THE SPILL. THE SPILL INCLUDED ONE APPROXIMATELY 10'X14' SPOT ON SOIL ON THE SOUTHWEST SHOULDER OF THE HIGHWAY AND APPROXIMATELY 150 TO 200 YARDS ON THE ROAD. THE PAINT ON THE HIGHWAY DRIED AND ALL THE WET PAINT AND CONTAMINATED DIRT WAS PUT INTO DRUMS. SAMPLES OF THE SOIL AND PAINT HAS BEEN TAKEN AND WILL BE TESTED. RESULTS OF THE SAMPLING WILL BE GIVEN TO TERESA SMITH FROM THE OFFICE OF EMERGENCY MANAGEMENT. ANY WASTE FORM THE CLEAN UP WILL BE SENT TO CHEM-COM/PERMA-FIX OF MEMPHIS FOR DISPOSAL. THE EMPLOYEE WAS REPRIMANDED AND RE-TRAINED TO PREVENT SUCH OCCURRENCES FROM HAPPENING AGAIN.

OUR TUCK WAS ON HIS WAY TO MAKING HIS SECOND DELIVERY OF THE  DAY, TO THE SAME CUSTOMER OF THE SAME PRODUCT. AFTER COMPLETING THE FIRST DELIVERY, THE TRUCK HAD TO TRAVEL A SHORT DISTANCE ON A PUBLIC ROAD TO THE SECOND DELIVERY SITE. THE DRIVER HEARD A NOISE WHEN HE GOT CLOSE TO THE TURN IN FOR THE SECOND DELIVERY SITE. HE STOPPED THE TRUCK AND DISCOVERED THAT THE RUPTURE DISK ON THE TANKER HAD BLOWN AND THAT 10-30 GALLONS OF MATERIAL HAD SPRAYED OUT. SPRAYED MATERIAL WENT ONTO THE PUBLIC ROAD, THE TOP OF THE TANKER TRUCK, 2 RESIDENTIAL MAILBOXES, 3 TRASH BARRELS, AND THE RAILING OF A PORCH ON A NEARBY HOUSE THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY CALLED IN TO HIS DISPATCHER SOME OF OUR PERSONNEL WERE SENT TO THE SITE AND LICENSED HAZARDOUS WASTE COMPANY WAS CALLED IN TO CLEAN UP THE SITE

A CLEANUP TEAM WAS IMMEDIATELY DISPATCHED TOT HE SITE IN ORDER TO CONTAIN THE SPILL AND TO PREVENT IT FROM BECOMING A MAJOR INCIDENT.  UPON INVESTIGATION IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT THE TANKER WHICH WAS LEASED TO OUR CUSTOMER BY A THIRD PARTY,  HAD AN UNCERTIFIED WELD AND THUS THIS WELD FAILED AND ALLOWED THE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL TO SPILL.  IN THE FUTURE WE WILL BE VERY SPECIFIC IN CHECKING THE CERTIFICATIONS OF TANKERS WHICH WE ARE ASKED TO PULL.

EMPLOYEE WAS FILLING OUR BULK FUEL TRUCK FOR DELIVERY TO A CUSTOMER. column168: CARRIER'S VEHICLE WAS NORTHBOUND ON I-95 IN REPORTED RAIN. WHILE CROSSING THE QUINNIPIAC RIVER BRIDGE THE DRIVER LOST CONTROL OF VEHICLE. IT JACKNIFED AND ROLLED ONTO ITS SIDE ACROSS ALL NORTHBOUND LANES OF THE HIGHWAY. THE VEHICLE CAME TO REST WITH ITS TRACTOR HANGING OVER THE BRIDGE. THE TRACTOR CAUGHT FIRE. CONNECTICUT STATE POLICE AND THE NEW HAVEN FIRE DEPARTMENT RESPONDED BUT WERE UNABLE TO REACH THE DRIVER. THE DRIVER DIED AS A RESULT OF THE INCIDENT. THE NORTHBOUND LANES OF I-95 WERE CLOSED AND REMAINED CLOSED FOR THE DURATION OF THE CLEAN UP-0720 APPROXIMATELY 1500 HOURS. BURNING DEBRIS FROM THE PLASTIC COMPONENTS OF THE CAB FELL ON TO VANS IN A PARKING LOT UNDER THE BRIDGE. FOUR VANS WERE TOTALLY DESTROYED AS A RESULT. THE LOT IS USED BY YALE UNIVERSITY AND THE VANS BELONG TO THEM. A REPRESENTATIVE OF THE CONNECTICUT DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL PROTECTION ARRIVED SHORTLY AFTER THE STATE POLICE AND FIRE DEPARTMENT. ACTING ON HIS OWN AUTHORITY, THE REPRESENTATIVE ENGAGED A NEARBY CONTRACTOR TO RESPOND AND HANDLE THE CLEAN UP. THE FIRST CONTRACTOR EMPLOYEE ARRIVED AT 0920. OTHER EMPLOYEES FOLLOWED. THEY SURVEYED THE LOAD TO DETERMINE THE EXTENT OF THE DAMAGES AND RELEASES.  DAMAGE TO AND RELEASE FROM PAILS OF THE N. JONAS CO. PRODUCT RESULTED IN ABOUT A DRUM OF WASTE BEING GENERATED IN ADDITION TO THE RUNOFF. THE MATERIAL MIXED WITH RAIN WATER AND BEGAN REACTING IN THE DRUM. DEP HAS ALLOWED THE MATERIAL TO REACT WHILE SPREAD OUT IN A ROLL OFF BOX THAT HAD BEEN BROUGHT TO THE SITE. AS OF 1120, THE TRAILER HAD BEEN OFF LOADED BY THE CONTRACTOR TO THE POINT WHERE THE N. JONAS CO. SHIPMENT WAS OFF. THE UNDAMAGED MATERIAL FROM THEIR SHIPMENT WAS RE-WRAPPED AND LOADED ONTO CONTRACTOR VEHICLES TO BE TAKEN TO THE CONTRACTOR'S  FACILITY.  A TOTAL OF 3 DUMPSTERS OF DEBRIS AND FREIGHT WERE GENERATED. ALL WERE TAKEN TO THE CONTRACTOR'S FACILITY.  ONE CONTAINS REACTING MATERIAL FROM THE N. JONAS SHIPMENT;  THIS ONE WILL BE SECURED AND ALLOWED TO REACT AT THE CONTRACTOR'S YARD.  THE FIRE DEPARTMENT ASKED THE CONTRACTOR TO CLEAN UP THE DEBRIS AND SPILLED FUEL IN THE LOT UNDER THE BRIDGE. AN ADDITIONAL 2 DRUMS WERE GENERATED FROM THAT OPERATION. THE CONTRACTOR CLEARED THE SCENE AT 1315. I-95 WAS REOPENED TO TRAFFIC AT ABOUT 1430.

column168: THE INCIDENT OCCURRED 26 JULY 2001 DURING UNLOADING OF FUEL OIL FROM THE CARRIER'S TANK TRAILER TO THE CONSIGNEE'S FUEL OIL STORAGE TANKS.  THE UNLOADING OF FUEL AT THIS FACILITY UTILIZES THE FACILITY'S FUEL PUMPS, WHICH ARE FED BY GRAVITY FROM THE DELIVERY VEHICLE.  ELECTRICAL MALFUNCTIONS IN THE DELIVERY SYSTEM CAUSED THE DELIVERY PUMP TO SHUT DOWN, UNBEKNOWNST TO THE DRIVER.  THE DESIGN OF THE DELIVERY SYSTEM PIPING ALLOWED FUEL TO SIPHON FROM THE TANK TRAILER AND DISCHARGE VIA A VENT INTO THE UNDERGROUND PUMP VAULT, WHICH WAS NOT VISIBLE TO THE DRIVER.  EFFORTS TO START THE PUMP FAILED AS THE VAULT FLOODED AND SHORTED THE MOTOR.  FUEL ESCAPED IN THE SURROUNDING SOIL THROUGH HOLES IN THE VAULT.  UPON DISCOVERY OF THE SPILL, THE DRIVER SECURED HIS TANK.  CONSIGNEE TOOK IMMEDIATE ACTION TO RECOVER THE REMAINING FUEL IN THE VAULT (APPROX. 1900 GALLONS) THEN HIRED A REMEDIATION CONTRACTOR TO ADDRESS SOIL AND GROUND WATER IMPACTS. CONSIGNEE COMPLETED UPGRADES TO THE FUEL DELIVERY SYSTEM TO PREVENT A RECURRENCE, HAS SINCE CEASED OPERATIONS.

AT AROUND 3:00 AM ON JULY 11, 2001, APPROXIMATELY 2000 GALLONS OF #4 OIL WAS OVERFILLED ON TANKER TRUCK 52-32.  IT APPEARS THAT IN THE PROCESS OF LOADING THE TANKER TRUCK, A VALVE THAT SHOULD HAVE BEEN CLOSED REMAINED OPEN.  THIS ALLOWED MATERIAL FROM TWO SEPARATE STORAGE TANKS TO FILL THE TANKER AT THE SAME TIME.  DUE TO THIS OVERSIGHT, THE TANKER FILLED FASTER THAN EXPECTED CREATING THE OVERFILL OF THE TANKER TRUCK.  AS SOON AS THE INCIDENT WAS NOTICED THE PUMP WAS SHUT OFF AND VALVES WERE CLOSED TO PREVENT FURTHER FILL OF THE TANKER TRUCK.  RELEASED MATERIAL WAS MOSTLY CONTAINED TO THE ASPHALT AND CONCRETE WITH A MINIMAL AMOUNT ENTERING THE STORM DRAIN.  THE STORM DRAIN RUNS INTO A TWO GATED WELL SYSTEM THAT PREVENTED THE MATERIAL FROM ENTERING NEARBY WATERWAYS.  ALL AREAS AFFECTED WERE CLEANED AND DECONTAMINATED USING CAUSTIC SOAP AND THE STORM DRAIN WAS PRESSURED WASHED.  AFTER THE INCIDENT WAS OVER AN INVESTIGATION REVEALED THAT THE LOADER WAS IN THE CONTROL ROOM USING THE ELECTRONIC READING OF THE STORAGE TANK TO MEASURE THE AMOUNT GOING INTO THE TANKER TRUCK.  THIS PRACTICE HAS BEEN STOPPED.  CURRENT PROCEDURES ARE THAT LOADING PERSONNEL MUST BE PRESENT AT THE TANKER TRUCK DURING ALL LOADING OPERATIONS.

HARRY RODABAUGH, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY MANAGER, WAS NOTIFIED AND CONFERRED WITH BATTALION CHIEF HUNTLEY, LAS VEGAS FIRE DEPARTMENT, WHO ADVISED MR. RODABAUGH THE PROPANE TANKCAR WAS LOCATED ON A SPUR TRACK NEAR THE SUBURBAN GAS COMPANY, VENTING GAS FROM THE RELIEF VALVE AT THE TOP OF  THE TANKCAR.CHIEF HUNTLEY ADVISED THE TEMPERATURE WAS ONE HUNDRED FOURTEEN DEGREES AND MR. RODABAUGH ADVISED CHIEF HUNTLEY ITS WAS A NORMAL PROCEDURE FOR THE TANKCAR TO VENT THE GAS AT ABNORMALLY HIGHER TEMPERATURES. CHIEF HUNTLEY ADVISED MR. RODABAUGH THE RELIEF VALVE WAS CONTINUOUSLY VENTING AND MR RODABAUGH ADVISED THIS WAS NOT NORMAL AND COULD POSSIBLE  BE A GAUGING ROD PROBLEM, RELIEF VALVE STUCK OPEN OR A DEFECTIVE O RING.JOHN, CHEMTREC, REPORTED HE CONTACTED GREG, SAFETY REPRESENTATIVE FOR PROFLAME, CONSIGNEE IN LAS VEGAS, NV. JOHN STATED GREG WAS EN ROUTE TO THE SUBURBAN GAS FACILITY AT 4520 MITCHELL ROAD TO INVESTIGATE THE INCIDENT AND ADVISE OF SERVICES AVAILABLE FROM HIS COMPANY TO ASSIST IN THE RESOLUTION OF THIS INCIDENT. MGR RODABAAUGH CONFERRED WITH PHIL GANNUSCIA, MANAGER OF TRAIN OPERATIONS, TO DISCUSS OFFLOADING THE TANKCAR TO ELIMINATE FURTHER PROBLEMS WITH THE VALVE RELEASE  LAS VEGAS FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS STILL ON SCENE AT THIS TIME. THE TANKCAR WAS ROLLED BACK INTO THE LOADING AREA OF "PROFLAME". THE LOADING CREW PLACED THE TANKCAR UNDER COOLING HOSES, COOLED THE CAR OFF AND STOPPED THE RELEASE. THE TANKCAR WAS SCHEDULE TO BE OF LOADED ON 07-04-01 IN THE AFERNOON.

column168: E.M.I. JOB NUMBER:  11343  A ONE GALLON JUG OF ACETIC ACID WAS FOUND LAYING ON ITS SIDE IN A SMALL POOL OF ACID.  THE PACKAGE WAS OPENED AND IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE LID WAS NOT TIGHT.  ONE-HALF GALLON OF LIQUID WAS RELEASED ONTO A SHEET OF PLYWOOD AND A PLYWOOD CRATE.  THE SPILLAGE WAS NEUTRALIZED/SOLIDIFIED USING BAKING SODA.  ALL OF THE BAKING SODA AND THE CARTON OF ACID WAS PLACED INTO A FIVE GALLON BUCKET FOR DISPOSAL.  E.M.I. WAS CONTACTED TO PROVIDE THE DISPOSAL SERVICES.

A CONWAY EMPLOYEE (CARL DOUGLAS) WAS 1/4 INTO THE TRAILER WHEN HE NOTICED THE SKID THAT HE HAD ON HIS FORKLIFT HAD A PUNCTURE ON ONE OF THE PAILS.  THE SPILLED PRODUCT WAS ALREADY DRIED AND HAD LEAKED ON THE SKID IT WAS LOADED ON TOP OF.  THE OTHER CONTAMINATED SKID WAS PART OF THE SAME SHIPMENT AND NO DUNNAGE OR LOAD RACK WAS USED TO SEPARATE THE DOUBLE STACKED SKIDS.  THE TWO DOUBLE STACKED SKIDS WERE LOADED SIDEWAYS AND PUSHED INTO A LOAD RACK WHICH HAD A SKID OVERLAPPING ON TOP OF THE LOAD RACK.  THE SKID FROM THE SHIPMENT LOADED ON TOP OF LOAD RACK IN FRONT OF THE DOUBLE STACKED SKIDS IS WHAT CAUSED THE PUNCTURE.  IT SEEMS THAT THE DSR WHOM LOADED THE SHIPMENT PUSHED THE SKIDS AGAINST THE LOAD RACK WITHOUT ANY REGARDS AS TO WHAT WAS IN FRONT.  IT WAS BROUGHT TO MY ATTENTION IMMEDIATELY, AND THE SHIPMENT WAS MOVED TO A EMPTY TRAILER AT THE END OF THE DOCK (SINCE IT WAS ALREADY ON HIS FORKLIFT) AND THE TRAILER WAS RED-TAGGED AND PULLED OUT TO THE YARD TO ISOLATE.  THE SAFETY SUPERVISOR AND INFOTRAC (EMERGENCY RESPONSE) WAS CALLED.  A LOCAL HAZMAT CLEANUP CO NAMED GARNER ENVIRONMENTAL WAS CALLED OUT TO RECOUP AND CLEAN THE SHIPMENT.

A PASSENGER CHECKED BOX WAS TRANSFERRED FROM SAN JUAN FLIGHT TO THE KANSAS CITY FLIGHT. THE CREW CHIEF NOTICED THE BOX HAD A STAIN AND IT SMELLED OF FUEL. AN ATTEMPT WAS MADE TO FIND THE PASSENGER BUT SHE MUST HAVE BEEN A MISCONNECT. THE BOX WAS INSPECTED AND INSIDE WAS SOME ALCOHOL, TEE SHIRTS, AND THREE SOUVENIR GLOBES. ONE HAD BROKEN OPEN AND LEAKED INSIDE THE BOX, THE FUEL SMELL WAS STRONGER ONCE THE BOX HAD BEEN OPENED. THE GLOBES WERE ANALYZED BY EAGLE ENVIRONMENTAL AND THEY DETERMINED THAT THE SMALL AMOUNT OF BLUE LIQUID WAS COLORED WATER. THE APPROXIMATELY 8-OZ OF CLEAR LIQUID WAS TESTED AS AROMATIC HYDROCARBONS (KEROSINE). WE ARE TRYING TO DETERMINE IF THE GLOBES ARE SOLD AT THE AIRPORT IN SAN JUAN OR IN THE CITY. NOTE: THERE ARE NO MARKINGS ON THE BOX TO INDICATE THAT IT CONTAINS A DANGEROUS GOOD. THE PASSENGER IN THIS CASE I'M SURE WAS TOTALLY UNAWARE.

column168: FILE:3081 D, SHIPPER: SIGMA-ALDRICH, AWE# ABE 26667163363 NCV. PART TIME HAZ MAT TECHNICIANS CECELIA HICKEY AND ELWOOD BOHL, AS WELL AS HAZARDOUS MATERIALS COORDINATOR MICHEAL FRYE DONNED PROPER PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT AND RESPONDED. UPON ARRIVAL THEY FOUND A BROWN FIBERBOARD BOX THAT WAS SUSPECTED TO BE EMITTING THE ODOR. THEY REMOVED THIS FROM THE AREA AND BEGAN THEIR INVESTIGATION.UPON THIS INVESTIGATION THEY FOUND THIS BOX TO CONTAIN 4 INNER FIBERBOARD BOXES, EACH CONTAINING A 2 L GLASS BOTTLE THESE INNER BOXES WERE ALL PACKED INSIDE A PLASTIC BAG. THIS PLASTIC BAG WAS SURROUNDED BY PACKING PEANUTS. NONE OF THE GLASS BOTTLES HAD POSITIVE MEANS TO SECURE THE LIDS, ONE OF WHICH WAS LOOSE CAUSING IT TO LEAK APPROXIMATELY 4 OUNCES.THEY REPLACED THE ITEMS INTO A RECOVERY DRUM AND RETURNED IT TO ALDRICH. THE BOXES WERE PROPERLY MARKED, LABELED, AND HAD THE APPROPRIATE HAZ CERTIFICATION ACCOMPANYING IT. THE AREA INVOLVED WITH THE ODOR WAS WELL VENTILATED BEFORE NORMAL WORK OPERATIONS WERE RESUMED. THERE WAS ONE EMPLOYEE IN CONTACT WITH THE ODOR. SHE WAS ADVISED WHAT IT WAS AND RETURNED TO HER WORK AREA NO MEDICAL ATTENTION WAS NEEDED, NO CHANGES REPORTED IN THIS EMPLOYEE, NO FOLLOW UP NEEDED. A COPY OF THE SHIPPER'S DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS WILL ACCOMPANY THIS REPORT. THERE ARE PICTURES ON FILE IN THE HAZ MAT OFFICE AT ILN. CLEAR OF SCENE 0103.

OUR DRIVER TIMOTHY FEKETE WAS UNLOADING THE HOSE FROM CUSTOMER'S LINE OUR DRIVER WAS HOLDING THE HOSE AND WAS TRYING TO HOLD IT STEADY SO HE COULD DRAIN PRODUCT INTO A BUCKET HOSE HAD NO CAP ON THE END OF IT. SOME PRODUCT WENT INTO THE BUCKET AND SOME DRIPPED OFF THE SIDE OF THE BUCKET AND WENT ON THE GROUND.

column168: DRIVER ALBERT LEWIS HAD JUST LEFT A FORMER CUSTOMER(CHICKASHEE) WHERE HE PICKED UP AN EMPTY TOTE TANK OF HYDROCHLORIC ACID.  ALBERT HAD LEFT THE CUSTOMER LOCATION PROCEEDING TO HIS NEXT STOP (APPROX. 1-MILE), WHILE CHECKING HIS MIRRORS HE NOTICED A SMALL WISP OF SMOKE COMING FROM THE SIDE OF HIS TRAILER.  ALBERT PULLED OFF TO THE SIDE OF THE ROAD GO OUT AND LOOKED, AT WHICH TIME HE NOTICED THE LIQUID DRIPPING FROM THE SIDE OF HIS TRAILER. ABOUT THE SAME TIME A GEORGIA STATE TROOPER PASSED BY AND OFFERED HIS ASSISTANCE. ONCE THE TROOPER SPOTTED THE PRODUCT DRIPPING HE ADVISED ALBERT LEWIS TO BACK AWAY UNTIL THE TIFTON HAZ-MAT TEAM ARRIVED.  ALBERT ADVISED THAT HE NEEDED TO AT LEAST TRY TO CONTAIN THE SPILL IN SOME WAY, BUT WAS ASKED TO WAIT ON THE HAZ-MAT TEAM. WHEN THE HAZ-MAT TEAM ARRIVED THE NEUTRALIZED THE SPILL WITH SODA  ASH, THEN COLLECTED THE SPENT MATERIAL AND PLACED DIRT ON THE AREA.  AFTER THIS THEY INSPECTED THE INTERIOR OF THE TRAILER AND FOUND THAT FRONT  PORTION OF THE TOTE TANK VALVE HAD BROKEN OFF. THE PRODUCT LOST WAS THE PRODUCT RESIDUE LEFT IN THE TOTE.  IT APPEARED THAT SOMEONE HAD EITHER STEPPED ON THE VALVE, OR A FORKLIFT MADE CONTACT WITH THE VALVE.  ONCE THE TOTE IS CLEANED AN INSPECTION OF EXACTLY WHY THE VALVE FAILURE OCCURRED WILL TAKE PLACE.  THE HAZ-MAT TEAM AND THE WAREHOUSE MANAGER ASSESSED THAT THE AREA WHERE THE SPILL OCCURRED WAS ABOUT 3'  IN DIAMETER, IT WAS FURTHER DETERMINED THAT APPROXIMATELY (2) GALLONS OF PRODUCT WAS LOST AND AT LEAST(1) GALLON OF PRODUCT WAS SPILLED TO THE GROUND. THE TRAILER WAS UNLOADED ON SITE AND PRODUCT TRANSFERRED TO ANOTHER TRAILER.  THE CONTAMINATED TRAILER WAS THEN TAKEN TO THE INTERSTATE NATIONAL LEASE(I.N.L) YARD WHERE OUR TRACTORS ARE LEASED.  THE OTHER TRAILER WAS SENT ON ITS WAY TO CONTINUE DELIVERIES.  THE CONTAMINATED TRAILER WAS TAKEN TO THE I.N.L YARD IN ALBANY ON 7/24/01 TO BE CLEANED AND RETURNED TO SERVICE. THE EXIT RAMP AT EXIT NUMBER(59) WAS TEMPORARILY CLOSED FOR CLEAN UP, AND NO FURTHER INCIDENTS TOOK PLACE AS A RESULT OF THIS MISHAP.  ALBERT LEWIS WAS CITED BY THE GEORGIA HIGHWAY PATROL $125 FOR FAILURE TO SECURE THE TOTE.

column168: FILE 2143 F & D, SHIPPER: SERENDIPITY ENTERTAINMENT, AWB#MCI 6930467968 CYP. THERE WAS ONE EMPLOYEE IN  CONTACT WITH THE ODOR, SHE WAS ADVISED WHAT IT WAS AND RETURNED TO HER WORK AREA, NO MEDICAL ATTENTION WAS NEEDED, NO CHANGES WERE REPORTED IN THIS EMPLOYEE, NO FOLLOW UP NEEDED. column168: WHILE CONDUCTING A ROUTINE COMPLIANCE INSPECTION AT CSX TRANSPORTATION'S RAILYARD AT BALDWIN, FL CSXT'S HAZARDOUS MATERIALS MANAGER, EG COOK (EGC), OBSERVED ACFX 86993 WITH A SLOW DRIP LEAK FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE. THE CAR WHICH CONTAINS A RESIDUE OF POTASSIUM HYDROXIDE SOLUTION WAS IN THE CAR SHOP FOR MECHANICAL REPAIRS WHEN IT WAS DISCOVERED TO HAVE A SLOW DRIP FROM THE TOP OF THE BELL CAP ON THE BOTTOM OPERATED BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE. THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE OPERATING HANDLE WAS PINNED IN THE CLOSED POSITION AND THE BELL CAP WAS WRENCH TIGHT.  THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE WAS OPENED AND CLOSED TO RESEAT IT.  THE AUXILIARY VALVE PLUG WAS REMOVED & PRODUCT WAS DRAINED FROM THE OUTLET EXTENSION PIPE.  THE OPENED AUXILIARY VALVE WAS OBSERVED FOR 5-8 MINUTES LATER AND THERE WAS NO FURTHER LEAKAGE.   THE AUXILIARY VALVE WAS CLOSED & SECURED. THE SECURED VALVE WAS INSPECTED TWENTY MINUTES LATER AND THERE WAS NO EVIDENCE OF PRODUCT LEAKAGE.  THE CAR WAS RELEASED.  EGC DISCUSSED INCIDENT WITH MR. MILES HAYNES, OCCIDENTAL ON 07/23/01 AND HE INDICATED THE BELL HOUSING GASKET WOULD BE REPLACED AND THE VALVE TESTED WHEN THE RECEIVED THE CAR BACK AT THEIR FACILITY.

DAN AKERS OF REAGENT STATED THAT THEY WOULD HAVE RESCAR RESPOND TO MAKE REPAIRS. RESCAR REPORTED THERE WAS SOME PRODUCT ON TOP OF THE CAR INDICATING LIQUID HAD SLOSHED OUT.  ALL THE SECUREMENT BOLTS WERE MADE WRENCH TIGHT.  THE VAPOR RELEASE STOPPED.  THE CAR WAS RELEASED.  RESCAR"S FINDING WERE DISCUSSED WITH MR. AKERS OF REAGENT AND HE INDICATED THAT HE INDICATED THAT HE WOULD INVESTIGATE WITH HIS LOADERS.

NO MEDICAL ATTENTION WAS NEEDED, NO CHANGES WERE REPORTED IN THIS EMPLOYEE, NO FOLLOW UP NEEDED THIS WAS PROPERLY MARKED, LABELED, AND HAD THE APPROPRIATE HAZ CERTIFICATION ACCOMPANYING IT. column168: ON JULY 12, 2001 DURING THE UPLOAD OF FLIGHT 989, OAKLAND (OAK) RAMP AGENTS IDENTIFIED AN ODOR IN THE BIN THAT SMELLED LIKE NAIL POLISH REMOVER.  THE FLIGHT WHICH ORIGINATES IN BURBANK (BUR) AND TERMINATES IN SEATTLE (SEA), TOOK A THIRTY-FIVE MINUTE DELAY IN OAK DUE TO THE SITUATION.  THE ODOR WAS COMING FROM A COOLER THAT WAS ACCEPTED AS CHECKED BAGGAGE.  THE CUSTOMER WAS QUESTIONED AS TO THE CONTENTS OF HER COOLER AND IDENTIFIED THE PRODUCT AS WELDWOOD CONTACT CEMENT.  THE MATERIAL DID NOT LEAK OUTSIDE OF ITS OUTER PACKAGE, BUT HAD SPILLED INSIDE THE COOLER.  THE AIRCRAFT WAS ALLOWED TO VENTILATE AND WAS RETURNED TO SERVICE AFTER MAINTENANCE AND THE CAPTAIN VERIFIED THERE WAS NO DAMAGE.  THE COOLER WAS TAKEN TO THE BAGGAGE SERVICE OFFICE, AND SOUTHWEST AIRLINES CORPORATE SAFETY WAS CONTACTED.  OAKLAND WAS INSTRUCTED TO CONTACT THE LOCAL (SFO) CASFO TO REPORT THE INCIDENT.  KERRI COUNTESS REPORTED THE INCIDENT TO SPECIAL AGENT KATHLEEN ROSHER.

column168: PULP & PAPER OF AMERICA'S ENVIRONMENTAL DEPARTMENT WAS NOTIFIED AT APPROXIMATELY 1515 ON 7/9/01, THAT A RAIL CAR #GATX 6351, WAS LEAKING SULFURIC ACID DOWN THE SIDES OF THE CAR AND RUNNING ONTO THE GROUND AND TRACKS.  UPON INSPECTION, IT APPEARED THAT THE RAIL CAR HAD BEEN OVERFILLED AND DUE TO EXPANSION FROM THE SUN, THE TANK WAS OVERFLOWING FROM THE TOP SEAL.  ST. LAWRENCE & ATLANTIC WAS CONTACTED.  UPON CONTACTING A MR. RICHARD ANDERSON, WITH ST. LAWRENCE, WE NOTIFIED HIM THAT RAIL CAR #GATX 6351 WAS LEAKING AND NEEDED TO BE STOPPED AND CLEANED UP.  HE BEGAN TRYING TO MAKE CONTACTS FROM HIS OFFICE IN MAINE.  ELMER LANG, WITH PPA, CALLED THE BERLIN FIRE DEPARTMENT AT APPROX. 1615 AND NOTIFIED THEM OF THE SPILL AND ASKED IF THEY HAD ANYTHING AVAILABLE TO HELP NEUTRALIZE THE ACID.  THEY SAID THEY DID NOT HAVE ANYTHING AND FELT THAT THERE WAS NO NEED TO RESPOND. WITH IMPENDING THUNDERSTORMS, PPA TOOK IT UPON THEMSELVES TO APPLY SAND TO THE CONTAMINATED AREA TO HELP PREVENT IT FROM MOVING.  AT 1645 ON 7/9/01, TAMMIE LAVOIE CONTACTED LT. VIENS AT THE BERLIN FIRE DEPARTMENT TO NOTIFY HIM THAT WE HAD COVERED THE SPILL AREA WITH SAND AND THAT THE TANK HAD STOPPED LEAKING.  AT APPROX. 1650, THE STATE POLICE WAS CONTACTED, WHO THEN CONTACTED MIKE WIMSATT FROM DES.  HE CONTACTED TAMMIE AT THE MILL AND WAS NOTIFIED OF THE EVENT.  ON 7/10/01, PPA'S ENVIRONMENTAL DEPARTMENT MET WITH JAMIE ROBINSON FROM ST. LAWRENCE & ATLANTIC ON HOW TO CLEAN UP THE SPILL AREA.  WE CALLED MIKE GALUSKA FROM THE SPILL INVESTIGATION UNIT AND HE SAID THAT WE COULD NEUTRALIZE THE AREA.  PPA THEN SPREAD DRY LIME ON THE AFFECTED AREA AND THE POURED WATER OVER THAT.  THE END RESULTING PH WAS 11. WHEN CAR #GATX 6351 WAS UNLOADED IN THE MILL, IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT THE FLANGE CONNECTED TO THE UNLOADING PIPE WAS NOT TIGHTENED DOWN.  THERE WAS NO DEFECT IN THE ACTUAL RAIL CAR.  IF THERE ARE ANY FURTHER QUESTIONS OR CONCERNS, PLEASE FEEL FREE TO CONTACT TAMMIE LAVOIE AT 603-342-2361.

column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 12AM ON 26-JULY-2001, A CHEMICAL SPILL WAS REPORTED TO THE SECOND SHIFT SUPERVISOR. A WET BOX WAS OBSERVED WHILE BREAKING DOWN A PALLET THAT WAS IN CROSS-DOCK STATUS. THE PRODUCT WAS IDENTIFIED AS BEING A WRIGHT MODIFIED STAIN PACK WHICH IS MADE UP 99% METHANOL. ONE SIXTEEN-OUNCE CONTAINER WITHIN A CASE HAD RUPTURED DURING TRANSPORT FROM THE DALLAS FACILITY (DO41). THE SECOND SHIFT SUPERVISOR EVACUATED THE BUILDING AND NOTIFIED THE WOODLANDS FIRE DEPARTMENT. A CHEMICAL RESPONSE TEAM RESPONDED TO THE FACILITY AT APPROXIMATELY 12:30AM AND BEGAN CLEAN-UP OPERATIONS. THE REMAINING HAZARDOUS CHEMICAL AND THE MATERIAL USED FOR CLEAN UP WAS PLACED INTO AN APPROVED HAZARDOUS WASTE CONTAINER AND PLACED IN THE FACILITY HAZARDOUS WASTE ACCUMULATION AREA. ONYX ENVIRONMENTAL WILL BE CONTACTED TO REMOVE AND DISPOSE OF THE MATERIAL IN THE NEAR FUTURE. THE TOTAL TIME FOR ABATING THE HAZARDOUS CHEMICAL AND ADEQUATELY VENTILATING THE AREA WAS APPROXIMATELY THREE HOURS. THERE WERE NO INJURIES INCURRED FROM THE SPILL, EVACUATION OR ABATEMENT PROCESS. THE PRODUCT WAS A LIMITED QUANTITY AND LEAKED DUE TO THE OUTER PACKAGE GIVING WAY DURING TRANSPORTAITON, WHICH IN TURN ALLOWED THE INNER CONTAINER TO CRUSH AND LEAK.

column168: DEAN C. COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS CONTACTED BY RMCC REPORTING A LEAKING TANK CAR AND RESULTING EMPLOYEE INJURY AT COLTON, CA. MANAGER COOPER CONTACTED MEFO DUFFY EXXON AND REQUESTED HE RESPOND TO THE LOCATION. MANAGER COOPER ALSO CONTACTED UNITED PUMPING, ONE OF THE RAILROAD'S HAZ MAT CONTRACTORS, AND REQUESTED THEY RESPOND WITH A TEAM FOR REMEDIATION OF THE SPILL. UPON HIS ARRIVAL, DEVELOPED ONE OF THE YARD SWITCHMEN HAD BEEN TRANSPORTED TO THE HOSPITAL FOR TREATMENT. THE SWITCHMAN HAD BEEN ALONG SIDE THE CAR WHEN IT WAS BEING MOVED DURING NORMAL SWITCHING OPERATIONS, AND WAS SPLASHED WITH PRODUCT FROM THE TANK CAR. IN COMPANY WITH SAN BERNARDIONO COUNTY HAZ MAT, AND UNITED PUMPING, THE CAR WAS INSPECTED. THE SIX SWING BOLTS THAT SECURE THE FILL HOLE COVER WERE FOUND LOOSE, AND COULD BE TURNED BY HAND. UPON OPENING THE FILL HOLE COVER PLATE, DEVELOPED THE NEOPRENE GASKET WAS BADLY DETERIORATED. HALF THE GASKET WAS SPLIT AROUND THE CENTER AREA SURFACE, PROVIDING NO SECUREMENT OF THE PRODUCT. A TEMPORARY GASKET WAS FORMED AND PLACED ON THE NOZZLE TO FORM A BARRIER BETWEEN THE NOZZLE AND THE COVER PLATE. THE SWING BOLTS WERE PROPERLY SECURED, AND THE CAR MOVED TO THE ONE SPOT, WHERE IT WAS PLACED ON BAD ORDER STATUS. THE SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED AND ADVISED THE CAR WOULD NEED THE PROPER GASKET INSTALLED PRIOR TO BEING MOVED ON TO DESTINATION. ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE THROUGH GATX TO REPLACE THE GASKET. NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE BY RMCC.

column168: AT 0900HRS ON 7-6-01 WHILE CONDUCTING COMPLIANCE INSPECTIONS, CTS MGR LERCH DETECTED A SLIGHT RELEASE OF VAPOR LEAKING FROM THE PRESSURE RELIEF VALVE ON LOADED TANK CAR MBLX 40174. CAR WAS LOCATED ON TRACK 46, COADY YARD, BAYTOWN, TX., UNION PACIFIC RAILROAD. UPON DETECTING RELEASE, MGR LERCH PRESSURED CHECKED CAR TO DETERMINE IF IT WAS OVERLOADED; PRESSURE MEASURED AT 170 PSI, AND GAUGED AT 21 INCHES OF OUTAGE. AFTER DETERMINING CAR WAS OVERLOADED,  MGR LERCH FURTHER INSPECTED THE PRESSURE RELIEF  VALVE  AND DETERMINED THE 0- RINGS TO BE FAULTY. MGR LERCH CONTACTED THE SHIPPER, EXXON CHEMICAL AND SPOKE TO MR FRED HOLZAPPEL, EMERGENCY RESPONSE COORDINATOR. HE IN TURN CONTACTED HIS RESOURCES AND ADVISED THAT A "VITON A" COMPOSITION O-RING WOULD BE THE REQUIRED REPLACEMENT O-RING. UPON REPLACEMENT OF THE O-RINGS, MGR LERCH APPLIED "SNOOP" LEAK DETECTOR TO THE VALVE, AND DETERMINED THAT THERE WAS NO FURTHER RELEASE OF PRODUCT. CAR WAS TAGGED THAT THE O-RINGS HAD BEEN REPLACED, AND WAS THEN RELEASED FOR TRANSPORTATION. THERE WERE NO DRAINS OR WATERWAYS IMPACTED AND NO REPORTED INJURIES RESULTING FROM THIS RELEASE. NOTIFICATIONS: 7-6-01, EXXON MOBIL CHEMICAL, FRED HOLZAPFEL EMERGENCY COORDINATOR; CHEM-TREC, NELSON, SPILL #20010706051.

A REPORT WAS RECEIVED THAT CONTAINER GCEU 484177 WAS LEAKING FROM THE FRONT END OF THE TRAILER. UPON INSPECTION IT WAS FOUND THAT DRUM NUMBER 53 WAS LEAKING FROM THE CENTER RIB DUE TO TWO DRUMS RUBBING TOGETHER AND CAUSING THE SMALL 1/16" HOLE WHICH WAS LEAKING ABOUT 1 DROP PER MINUTE. TWO GALLONS LEAKED ON THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER AND ONE GALLON ONTO THE GROUND. THE LEAK SEALED ITSELF. THESE WHERE CLOSED TOP DRUMS, THERE WAS CARDBOARD ON THE FLOOR UNDER 3 DRUMS WHICH CAUSED IT TO RAISE AND TURN, WHICH IN TURN CREATED THE HOLE AND CAUSED THE LEAK. APL/ASHLAND CHEMICAL RESPONDED WITH THERE HAZMAT TEAM FOR CLEANUP AND TRANSLOADING OF THIS TRAILER. NO PI'S, NO WATERWAYS, OR DRAINS EFFECTED.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Abrasion; Inadequate Blocking and Bracing
column168: DEAN C. COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS CONTACTED BY RMCC REPORTING A LEAKING CONTAINER AT THE ICTF, LONG BEACH, CA. MANAGER COOPER DROVE TO THE ICTF AND LOCATED THE ABOVE CONTAINER IN RED ROW, SPACE 225. THE 20 FOOT CONTAINER WAS PLACARED FLAMMABLE AND CORROSIVE, AND NOTED LEAKING FROM THE NOSE OF THE CONTAINER. A SMALL POOL OF LIQUID, LESS THAN 1 GALLON, WAS ON THE PAVEMENT BELOW THE CONTAINER. THE PRODUCT WAS FIELD TESTED AND FOUND TO HAVE SOME FLAMMABLE CHARACTERISTICS AND PH TESTED NEUTRAL. THE CONTAINER WAS MOVED TO THE CUSTOMS DOCK WHERE IT COULD BE ISOLATED PENDING INSPECTION. INSPECTION NOTED THE BLOCKING AND BRACING CONSISTED OF 3 SETS OF 2X6 LUMBER ACROSS THE REAR IN A X PATTERN. THIS IS NOT A RECOMMENDED PROTOCOL FOR THE SECUREMENT OF HAZARDOUS COMMODITIES, NOR IS IT AN APPROVED METHOD PER THE AAR BOE PAMPHLET 6C FOR PROPER SECUREMENT VIA RAIL TRANSPORT. THE SHIPPER ARRANGED TO HAVE THE CONTENTS TRANSLOADED AND INSPECT FOR THE SUSPECT LEAKER. LOCATED ONE DRUM IN THE NOSE ROW OF THE CONTAINER, SECOND OUT FROM THE RIGHT SIDE WALL, THAT HAD ABRADED AGAINST THE FRONT WALL OF THE CONTAINER, WHICH DAMAGED THE TOP AND BOTTOM ROLLING HOOPS, ALLOWING THE CONTENTS TO BE RELEASED. THE DRUM WAS PATCHED AND PLACED INTO AN OVER PACK FOR SECUREMENT. THE FLOORING WAS CLEANED OF THE RESIDUE, AND THE LADING PLACED BACK INTO THE ORGINAL CONTAINER. ONCE PROPERLY SECURED, THE CONTAINER WAS RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT ONTO THE CONSIGNEE. THE DAMAGED DRUM WAS HELD OUT PENDING INSTRUCTIONS FROM THE MANUFACTURER TO RETURN IT TO THE POINT OF ORIGIN. NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE BY RMCC.

column42: PETROLEUM DISTILLATES, N.O.S. OR PETROLEUM PRODUCTS, N.O.S.
column168: NATX 29568 WAS REPORTED LEAKING FORM THE MANWAY WHENEVER THE CAR WAS MOVED. INSPECTION BY EMG MANAGER, PAUL PERSON, REVEALED THE MANWAY COVER GASKET WAS THE OLD ASBESTOS TYPE WHICH ARE NOT TO BE USED ANY MORE. THE GASKET WAS REPLACED AND THE CAR WAS SECURED AND RELEASED FOR TRANSPORTATION TO DESTINATION.

ON 7/12/01 IT WAS REPORTED TO KIM KEELING MANAGER OF ENVIRONMENTAL FIELD OPS. THAT CONTAINER NOSU 222375 WAS LEAKING A RED SUBSTANCE. UPON ARRIVAL AT THE SCENE MR. KEELING OBSERVED RED FLUID COMING FROM THE TRAILER. FOUR 55 GALLON DRUMS LEANING AGAINST THE DOORS FELL OUT WHEN THE DOORS WERE OPENED. BLOCKING AND BRACING EXCEPTIONS WERE NOTED. THE SHIPPER, AMERICAN PRESIDENT INTERMODAL, WAS CONTACTED (PATRICK WIGEL) AND ASKED TO PROVIDE A CONTRACTOR TO HANDLE REMEDIATION. MR. KEELING ENTERED THE TRAILER, FOUND THE LEAKING DRUM AND PATCHED THE HOLE TO CONTAIN THE REST OF THE CONTENTS OF THE DRUM. ONE DRUM HAD BEEN DENTED AND WAS LEAKING FROM THE CREASE. (PINHOLE). THIS DRUM WAS LOCATED IN THE FRONT END OF THE TRAILER AND HAD APPARENTLY BEEN DAMAGED WHILE BEING LOADED. RMCAT WAS CONTRACTED TO RESPOND TO THE INCIDENT. ON 7/13/2001 RMCAT OFFLOADED THE DRUMS, PUT THE LEAKER IN AN OVERPACK AND RELOADED THE TRAILER. THE TRAILER HAD PREVIOUSLY BEEN BLOCKED AND BRACED WITH AN ADHESIVE TYPE TAPE THAT WRAPPED AROUND THE END OF THE TIERS TO SECURE THE BARRELS. RMCAT SECURED THE LOAD WITH LUMBER BLOCKING AND BRACING AND RELEASED THE TRAILER TO TRANSPORTATION. THE OVERPACK AND THE CLEANED UIP WASTE WAS RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER BY RMCAT.

column168: ACFX 87676 A LOAD FROM MEXICO THAT HAD A LEAKING BOTTOM OUTLET CAP. THE LEAK WAS STOPPED AND BNSF WAS NOTIFIED REGARDING THE OTHER PROBLEMS WITH THE CAR. WE ALSO REQUESTED THEY NOTIFY THEIR CUSTOMER.

column42: ACETIC ACID, GLACIAL OR ACETIC ACID SOLUTION, WITH MORE THAN 80 PERCENT ACID, BY MASS
column168: KENNETH SIMPSON, MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY WAS INSPECTING TANK CARS WHEN HE FOUND TANK CAR ETCX21030 LEAKING. THE LEAK WAS COMING FROM THE SAMPLE VALVE. INSPECTION REVEALED THE VALVE WAS OPEN AND THE PLUG WAS LOOSE. MGR. SIMPSON CLOSED THE VALVE AND TIGHTENED THE PLUG. THE TANK CAR WAS RELEASED TO TRANSPORTATION.

ANDREW TRIPP, YARDMASTER, REPORTED CARMEN RECEIVED THROAT IRRITATION WHEN THEY CAME INTO CONTACT WITH TANKCAR GATX 49650. THIS TANKCAR WAS PARKED ON THE EAST END OF THE OGDEN RAIL YARD. REGIONAL MANAGER SIROTEK, REGIONAL MANAGER DISCUSSED THE TANK CAR INSPECTION AND POSSIBLE REPAIR WITH JOHN OTTO, BRUSH WELLMAN. RICK SLOANE, MANAGER CTS CONTRACTED PAC WEST ENVIRONMENTAL, CONTRACTOR, TO INSPECT AND REPAIR THE TANK CAR. PAC WEST RESPONSE TEAM FOUND THE LIQUID LINE VALVE, ON THE B-END OF THE TANK CAR PARTIALLY OPEN AND THE CLOSURE PLUG NOT WRENCH TIGHT. THE VALVE AND PLUG WERE SECURED AND THE TANK CAR RELEASED. CHEMTREC WAS NOTIFIED.

MGR. C.T.S. R. SLOANE WAS NOTIFIED BY RMCC OF AN INTERMODAL CONTAINER LEAKING AT THE SEATTLE, WA., INTERMODAL RAMP. column168: RMCC CONTACTED CTS MGR. M. KELLY REFERENCE THE ABOVE TANK CAR. RMCC ADVISED THAT THEY HAD RECEIVED A CALL FROM THE MTO K. NORRIS WHO ADVISED THAT HE HAD OBSERVED THE ABOVE CAR SPLASHING LIQUID OUT THE TOP WHEN THE CAR WAS MOVED. NORRIS ADVISED THAT HE HAD ISOLATED THE CAR UNTIL SOMEONE COULD REPAIR IT. KELLY PROCEEDED TO THE LOCATION OF THE CAR. WHEN HE ARRIVED HE INSPECTED THE CAR AND FOUND THAT THE VACUUM RELIEF VALVE HAD BEEN REMOVED FROM THE MANWAY COVER AND WAS LAYING ON THE TOP OF THE CAR NEAR THE CAT WALK AREA. KELLY REPLACED THE VACUUM RELIEF VALVE AND RELEASED THE CAR TO CONTINUE ONTO ITS DESTINATION. CHEMTREC AND THE SHIPPER WERE BOTH CONTACTED.

DEVELOPED ALL 8 OF THE MANWAY SWING BOLTS WERE LOOSE AND COULD BE TURNED BY HAND. THE SWING BOLTS WERE PROPERLY SECURED AND THE CAR RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT ONTO THE CONSIGNEE.
