column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Water Damage
column168: DEAN C. COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS CONTACTED BY RMCC REPORTING A LEAKING TANK CAR AT COLTON, CA. MANAGER COOPER DEVELOPED THE ABOVE CAR WAS IN THE RECEIVING YARD WHERE THE CAR DEPARTMENT NOTED LIQUID DRIPPING FROM THE SIDE OF THE CAR. MANAGER COOPER CONTACTED UNITED PUMPING, THE RAILROADS LOCAL HAZ MAT CONTRACTOR, AND HAD THEM RESPOND TO INVESTIGATE THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK. DEVELOPED ALL 6 OF THE MANWAY SWING BOLTS WERE LOOSE AND COULD BE TURNED BY HAND. IT ALSO APPEARED THAT PRODUCT HAD ESCAPED FROM THE VACUUM RELIEF VALVE MOUNTED ON TOP OF THE MANWAY COVER PLATE. THE MANWAY BOLTS WERE TIGHTENED AND THE CAR SET TO THE RIP TRACKS PENDING FURTHER INSPECTION. CHEVRON WAS CONTACTED AND ADVISED TO HAVE THE LOCAL GATX MOBIL UNIT INSPECT THE VACUUM BREAKER PRIOR TO THE CAR CONTINUING IN TRANSIT. GATX INSPECTED THE CAR AND FOUND THE VACUUM BREAKER TO BE FUNCTIONING PROPERLY. THE MANWAY GASKET WAS REPLACED AND THE CAR SECURED FOR MOVEMENT ONTO THE CONSIGNEE. NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE BY RMCC.

JOHN MILLER, MGR. ENVIRONMENTAL FIELD OPERATIONS WAS ADVISED THAT TANKCAR CGTX 68001 WAS VENTING VAPORS FROM ITS SAFETY RELIEF VALVE. RICHARD WULFF MS OF THE A&S RAILROAD HAD THE CAR ISOLATED AND CONTACTED THE SHIPPER (JD IRVING LTD). AFTER INVESTIGATING, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE WAS OPERATING PROPERLY AND THE CAR WAS OVERLOADED, THEREBY CAUSING PRESSURE TO BUILD INSIDE THE TANK. ANOTHER CAR WAS OBTAINED AND THE LOAD WAS PARTIALLY TRANSFERRED WHICH RELIEVED THE PRESSURE IN THE CAR. BOTH CARS WERE RELEASED TO THE SHIPPER.

column58: Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug); Manway or Dome Cover; Piping or Fittings
column168: LANE A. SEKAVEC, MANAGER-CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY WAS NOTIFIED A LEAKING TANK CAR IN THE 18TH STREET YARD. THERE WERE TWO CARS THAT WERE SUSPECT AND IT WAS NOT IMMEDIATELY KNOWN WHICH CAR WAS CAUSING THE PROBLEM. MR. SEKAVEC AND REPRESENTATIVES FROM HAZ-MAT RESPONSE ARRIVED ON SCENE AND BEGAN ASSESSMENT OF THE TWO CARS. THE FIRST CAR CHECKED WAS CITX35258, WHICH HAD NO DETECTABLE PROBLEMS. THE SECOND-CAR, BADX1001, WAS CHECKED AND THERE WAS A FAINT ODOR OF ANHYDROUS AMMONIA WAS PICKED UP AT GROUND LEVEL. THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING COVER WAS OPENED AND AN ODOR OF ANHYDROUS AMMONIA WAS DETECTED THERE AS WELL. ALL THE VALVES AND FITTINGS WERE CHECKED WITH SNOOP LEAK DETECTOR WITH NOTHING REMARKABLE BEING FOUND. THE CAR WAS SECURED AND MOVED A SHORT DISTANCE TO A SECLUDED AREA OF THE YARD WHERE IT WAS BLUE FLAGGED AND LOCKED OUT FOR PROTECTION. THE CAR WAS AGAIN EVALUATED FOR LEAKS WITH NONE BEING READILY FOUND. THE DRAIN HOLES WERE PLUGGED IN THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING AND WATER POURED INTO THE HOUSING TO FLOOD AREA TO SEE IF THERE WERE ANY LEAKS OF PRODUCT COMING FROM AREAS THAT WERE INACCESSIBLE TO THE LEAK DETECTION MATERIAL, WITH NONE BEING FOUND. THE DETERMINATION WAS MADE THAT THE LEAK HAD TO BE COMING FROM BETWEEN THE PRESSURE PLATE AND THE TANK CAR NOZZLE, AS THERE WERE NO OTHER PLACES THAT COULD BE LEAKING. THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED AS TO THE PROBLEM WITH THE CAR AND RESTRICTIONS ON MOVING IT IN ITS CONDITION. THE DECISION WAS MADE TO OFF LOAD THE CAR TO TANK TRUCKS. THE FOLLOWING MORNING, THE TRANSFER WAS STARTED TO MOVE THE PRODUCT TO THE TANK TRUCKS. FOLLOWING THE REMOVAL OF THE ANHYDROUS AMMONIA, THE VAPORS WERE SCRUBBED OFF THROUGH A TANK OF WATER TO FORM AN AQUEOUS NITROGEN SOLUTION THAT THE SHIPPER WILL REPROCESS. THE TANK CAR WAS SECURED FOLLOWING THE TRANSFER AND THE SHIPPER NOTIFIED. THE SHIPPER WAS ALSO ADVISED ABOUT GETTING A ONE-TIME MOVEMENT EXEMPTION, AS THE CAR NO LONGER MET SPECIFICATIONS.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Inadequate Blocking and Bracing; Too Much Weight on Package
column168: DAVE JACKSON, SPECIAL AGENT HAZMAT, RECEIVED A REPORT FROM RMCC CONCERNING A LEAKING CONTAINER AND EMPLOYEE WITH POSSIBLE CHEMICAL BURNS AT THE UP RAMP, LATHROP CA. CONTAINER PATU 440882 WAS FOUND LEAKING FROM THE FRONT OF THE CONTAINER. A PH TEST WAS CONDUCTED AND THE TEST SHOWED A PH OF 14. THE LOAD WAS INSPECTED AND FOUND TO HAVE NO BLOCKING OR BRACING TO SECURE THE PALLETS. SCORING ON THE CONTAINER FLOOR SHOWED MOVEMENT OF 24-36 INCHES. THE INJURED EMPLOYEE WASHED AND FLUSHED THE AREA OF HIS RIGHT INNER ARM AND DID NOT REQUIRE ANY MEDICAL ATTENTION DUE TO HIS QUICK ACTIONS. THE LOAD WAS TRANSLOADED AND CLEANED. THE FLATCAR AND CONTAINER THAT WAS STACKED BENEATH WERE DECONTAIMINATED BY MORGAN ENVIRONMENTAL.

column42: PETROLEUM GASES, LIQUEFIED OR LIQUEFIED PETROLEUM GAS
column168: TIM O'BRIEN, REGIONAL MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS NOTIFIED BY RMCC OF A TANK CAR VENTING AT THE UP COADY YARD IN BAYTOWN, TEXAS. HE RESPONDED AND FOUND TANKCAR GATX62084 VENTING FROM THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE. PRESSURE ON THE CAR WAS 160 PSI AND THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE WAS SET AT 300 PSI. OUTAGE ON THE CAR WAS 1". O'BRIEN DISCUSSED HIS FINDINGS WITH MR. MCKENZIE WHO ARRANGED FOR A TRUCK TO BE DISPATCHED TO THE YARD TO REDUCE THE AMOUNT OF LADING IN THE CAR. MARTIN TRUCKING RESPONDED TO COADY YARD AND APPROXIMATELY 2,000 GALLONS OF LADING WAS REMOVED FROM THE TANKCAR WHICH NOW HAD AN OUTAGE OF 15". FURTHER INSPECTION OF THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE FOUND THE O-RING TO BE OUT OF PLACE AND OUT-OF-ROUND. O'BRIEN REPLACED O-RING ON THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE AND RELEASED THE CAR.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Inadequate Blocking and Bracing
column168: DAVE JACKSON, SPECIAL AGENT HAZMAT, RECEIVED A REPORT FROM LATHROP MANAGER LOREEN GASTINEAU REGARDING A MIXED HAZARDOUS LOAD LEAKING AT THE UP FACILITY, LATHROP CA. PRIOR TO HIS NOTIFICATION, ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGER, JIM LEVY HAD ALREADY CONTACTED MORGAN ENVIRONMENTAL, A RAILROAD CONTRACTOR, TO RESPOND. UPON SAHM JACKSON'S ARRIVAL, SAN JOAQUIN COUNTY PUBLIC HEALTH SPECIALIST ALISON YOUNGBLOOD WAS ON THE SCENE. DUE TO A MIXED LOAD OF ACIDS AND FLAMMABLE, THREE MEN DONNED APPROPRIATE PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT TO BRING THE LOAD OFF THE TRAIN AND CHECK THE SHIPMENT. THE LOAD WAS INSPECTED AND A 275 GALLON TOTE AT THE REAR OF CONTAINER WAS FOUND LEAKING. THE TOTE HAD CRACKED AT THE TOP OF THE LOAD LEAKING APPROXIMATELY 70 GALLONS OF PRODUCT. THE LOAD WAS IMPROPERLY SECURED WITH TYGUARD AT THE DOOR. THE TOTE SUPPORT CAGE HAD ALSO CRACKED AT THE BOTTOM. THE CONTENTS OF THE TRAILER WERE TRANSLOADED INTO ANOTHER CONTAINER AND THE CONTAINER WAS CLEANED. THE CONTAINER BELOW APLU 881466 AND THE FLATCAR WERE BOTH DECONTAMINATED BY MORGAN ENVIRONMENTAL.
column172: Composite, with a rigid plastic inner receptacle for liquids and a steel outer packaging

column168: THE UNION PACIFIC RAILROAD CHEYENNE, WY CORRIDOR MANAGER, REPORTED AN UNKNOWN AMOUNT OF PRODUCT WAS RELEASED FROM THE TOP OF TANKCAR GATX 30826 ENTRAINED ON TRAIN MNPHK 20. THE CORRIDOR MANAGER STATED THAT THE LEAK WAS NOTED ON A ROLLBY AND THE TRAIN WOULD BE SET OUT ON THE EDSON SIDING FOR INSPECTION. GARY HONEYMAN, MANAGER OF ENVIRONMENTAL SITE REMEDIATION, WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED WITH EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR ROCKY MOUNTAIN CATASTROPHE. MARK REIMERS, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY REGIONAL MANAGER WAS ALSO INFORMED. GARY HONEYMAN, MANAGER OF ENVIRONMENTAL SITE REMEDIATION, REPORTED HIMSELF AND ROCKY MOUNTAIN CATASTROPHE, WERE ON SCENE AND REPAIRED THE LEAK BY TIGHTENING DOWN THE LIQUID VALVE. IT APPEARED THAT THE VALVE HAD BEEN RECENTLY APPLIED TO THE CAR, BUT HAD NOT BEEN TIGHTENED DOWN, RESULTING IN A SMALL LEAK. NO PRODUCT REACHED THE GROUND. RMCAT WASHED THE PRODUCT FROM THE TANK CAR AND DISPOSED OF THE WASTE APPROPRIATELY. THE CAR WAS THEN RELEASED FOR TRANSPORTATION.

DEAN C. COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS CONTACTED BY RMCC REPORTING A LEAKING TANK CAR AT COLTON, CA. DEVELOPED THE CAR DEPARTMENT WAS INSPECTING TRACK #301 IN THE DEPARTURE YARD AND NOTED THE ABOVE TANK CAR DRIPPING PRODUCT FROM THE CENTER BOTTOM AREA OF THE CAR. MANAGER COOPER DROVE TO THE LOCATION AND NOTED PRODUCT DRIPPING FROM THE WELD AROUND THE BOTTOM SUMP. THE SUMP IS PROTECTED WITH A SKID PLATE WHICH LIMITED ACCESS. THE SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED AND ADVISED THE CAR APPEARED TO HAVE FAILED AND THE PRODUCT WOULD HAVE TO BE TRANSFERED. THE SHIPPER CONTACTED THEIR LOCAL FACILITY, KEMIRON, FONTANA, WHO PROVIDED TRANSFER TRUCKS AND PUMPS TO OFF LOAD THE PRODUCT. ONCE THE CAR WAS MADE EMPTY, IT WAS SET TO THE GATX TANK CAR FACILITY, COLTON, FOR CLEANING AND INSPECTION TO DETERMINE THE EXACT CAUSE OF THE FAILURE. NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE BY RMCC.

column58: Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug); Manway or Dome Cover; Piping or Fittings
column168: TIM O'BRIEN, REGIONAL MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS NOTIFIED BY RMCC OF LEAKING TANKCAR TILX 260128 AT STRANG YARD. HE RESPONDED AND FOUND ALL EIGHT SWING BOLTS FOR THE MANWAY COVER PLATE LAYING DOWN. SECURED MANWAY COVER PLATE AND NOTIFIED SHIPPER. SHIPPER SENT A CREW TO SITE AND THEY DECONTAMINATED CAR WHERE SPILLAGE OCCURRED. INFORMED THEM THAT THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE WAS OUT OF DATE. THEY PROVIDE CERTIFICATE INDICATING SAFETY RELIEF VALVE WAS COMPLIANT, BUT THE STENCIL HAD NOT BEEN UPDATED. THEY RESTENCILLED THE CAR AND IT WAS RELEASED TO TRANSPORTATION..

column42: PETROLEUM GASES, LIQUEFIED OR LIQUEFIED PETROLEUM GAS
column168: L.D. LIBBY, SR. SPECIAL AGENT HAZ/MAT II, WAS ADVISED TANKCAR PLMX 34103 WAS ON SPOT AT FERRELL GAS, 309 N FRUITLAND, KENNEWICK, WA. AND WAS LEAKING FROM THE TOP. FURTHER, FIRE DEPARTMENT CHIEF WAS ON THE SCENE. CHIEF DENNIS WATERS ADVISED THE TANKCAR WAS LEAKING VAPOR AT THE TOP OF THE CAR, UNDER THE PRESSURE PLATE. HE FURTHER ADVISED HE COULD NOT SEE ANY PRODUCT, HOWEVER HE COULD SMELL IT. CHIEF WATERS AND JIM KLOEHN, FERRELL GAS PLANT MANAGER WERE ADVISED TO BLANKET THE TANK CAR WITH COLD WATER IN ORDER TO LOWER THE TEMPERATURE AND INTERNAL PRESSURE OF THE TANK CAR. THEY WERE ALSO ADVISED TO OFF LOAD THE TANK CAR ONCE THE TEMPERATURE AND PRESSURE WERE LOWERED. MARK DETTOFF, OPS MANAGER, FERRELL GAS, KENNEWICK, WA.ADVISED THAT TANKCAR PLMX 34103 WAS SUCCESSFULLY UNLOADED BETWEEN 1725 HRS 07/23 AND 0200 HRS.,07/24/2001.

column58: Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug); Manway or Dome Cover; Piping or Fittings
column168: JERMAINE JOHNSON, MANAGER OF YARD OPERATIONS, REPORTED A TANKCAR WAS LEAKING AND HAD BEEN ISOLATED ON TRACK 875 OF THE YUMA YARD. DENNIS JOHNSON, MANAGER OF CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED ALONG WITH RAILROAD CONTRACTOR, ERI, FROM PHOENIX, AZ. MGR JOHNSON WAS CONFERRED WITH HENRY LISERIO, DIAMOND SHAMROCK, WHO REPORTED THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT HAD ESTIMATED THE LEAK AT ONE GALLON A LIQUID LINE AT THE TOP OF THE CAR. MR. LISERIO PROVIDED 210-679-7500 AS A 24 HOUR EMERGENCY NUMBER FOR DIAMOND SHAMROCK. UPON ARRIVAL, MANAGER JOHNSON INSPECTED THE TANK CAR AND SECURED THE LIQUID LINE CAP, WHICH HAD BEEN IMPROPERLY SECURED. THE TANK CAR WAS RELEASED TO CONTINUE TO DESTINATION. THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED.

KENNETH SIMPSON, MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY WAS CONTACTED BY RMCC ABOUT A LEAKING TANK CAR GATX7737 AT THE SHREVEPORT YARD, LA. SPECIAL AGENT ED FREDFICK WAS ALSO CONTACTED AND RESPONSED TO THE SCENE. ED FOUND THAT THE RUPTURE DISC ON THE TANK CAR HAD FAILED. ED AND LOUISIANA STATE POLICE OFFICER, ED BOBBIT REPLACED THE FAILED RUPTURE DISC AND THE TANK CAR WAS RELEASED TO CONTINUE TO DESTINATION.

RMCC WAS ADVISED BU JANET, LA CHEMICALS THAT TANK CAR GATX 61117 ON SPOT AT THEIR FACILITY HAD BEEN DISCOVERED WITH A SEAL LEAKING DURING THE UNLOADING PROCESS. SHE ADVISED THAT THIS WAS ONLY A COURTESY NOTIFICATION AND THAT A REPRESENTATIVE FROM ANOTHER LA CHEMICAL PLANT WOULD BE RESPONDING TO MAKE THE NECESSARY REPAIRS. MIKE COATS, LCI LIMITED,THE SHIPPER, REPORTED HE WAS AWARE OF THE PROBLEM AND ADVISED THAT RESCAR, A CONTRACTOR WOULD RESPOND. MR. COATS REPORTED THIS WAS MAINTENANCE PROBLEM AND INVOLVED A BED SEAL. HARRY RODABOUGH, MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, AND CHEMTREC WERE NOTIFIED.

KENNETH SIMPSON, MGR CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS ADVISED BY THE NORTH LITTLE ROCK CONTROL CENTER THAT THE ABOVE TANK CAR THAT HAD A FOUL ODOR COMING FROM IT. MANAGER SIMPSON'S INSPECTION REVEALED THAT THE SAMPLE VALVE WAS OPEN AND THE PLUG WAS CROSS THREADED. HE TAPED THE THREADS ON THE SAMPLE VALVE AND PUT IN A NEW PLUG. HE ALSO CLOSED THE SAMPLE VALVE. THE TANK CAR WAS RELEASED TO TRANSPORTATION.

column42: BUTYLENE SEE ALSO PETROLEUM GASES, LIQUEFIED
column168: HARRY RODABAUGH, MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION, REPORT DERAILMENT OF TRAIN YRO60 06 WHICH DERAILED TANKCARS GATX 59298, RTMX 13122, AND WRNX 030069. WRNX 30069 WAS DAMAGED AS A RESULT OF THE DERAILMENT, BUT NOT DERAILED. TANKCAR WRNX 030069 WAS INSPECTED AND FOUND TO BE LEAKING, NOT AS THE RESULT OF THE DERAILMENT. SLIGHT VAPOR LEAK FOUND AT THE PACKING GLAND NUT. THIS WAS REPAIRED BY MGR. RODABOUGH. CHEMTREC WAS NOTIFIED.

AT 1450HRS ON 7-28-01, CTS MGR LERCH WAS CONTACTED BY THE RISK MANAGEMENT COMMUNICATION CENTER, AND ADVISED OF A LEAKING TANK CAR ENTRAINED ON TRAIN MBVEW-24, LOCATED ON SIDING TRACK AT MILE POST 339.4, ANGELTON SUBDIVISION. CAR WAS REPORTED BY A BURLINGTON NORTHERN EMPLOYEE WHO WAS DRIVING BY AND NOTED PRODUCT LEAKING FROM THE CAR. UPON ARRIVAL, MGR LERCH NOTED NO PRODUCT LEAKING FROM THE CAR. CLOSER INSPECTION DID HOWEVER REVEAL THAT THERE WERE SIGNS THAT THE CAR HAD LEAKED A SMALL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT FROM THE COMBINATION HOUSING WHICH HOUSES THE AIR AND LIQUID VALVES. MGR LERCH CHECKED AND NOTED ALL VALVES AND FITTINGS TO BE TIGHT, AND THAT THE CAR WAS IN DOT COMPLIANCE FOR TRANSPORTATION. AFTER DETERMINING THAT THE CAR WAS SECURED, MGR LERCH RELEASED CAR TO CONTINUE ONTO DESTINATION. DUE TO THE UNUSUAL NATURE OF THE CALL, AND LACK OF KNOWING WHO HAD REPAIRED THE CAR, MGR LERCH SPOKE TO A LOCAL NEIGHBOR. HE INDICATED THAT A WHITE TRUCK WITH SEVERAL PEOPLE HAD WORKED ON THE CAR EARLIER THAT AFTERNOON BECAUSE OF THE LEAK. THERE WERE NO SPECIFIC IDENTIFYING MARKS ON THE CAR EXCEPT FOR THE WORDS "EMERGENCY LEAK REPAIR" WRITTEN ON THE SIDE OF IT. ON 7-30-01, MGR LERCH CONTACTED THE SHIPPER AND SPOKE TO CAROL KAPLITA, SENIOR RAIL COORDINATOR AND TERRY BRICE, HAZMAT MANAGER. BOTH INDICATED THEY HAD NO KNOWLEDGE OF THE CAR BEING WORKED ON, NOR WERE THEY ABLE TO FIND OUT WHO WORKED ON THE CAR AFTER CHECKING THEIR RECORDS AND RESOURCES.

MANAGER ENVIRONMENTAL FIELD OPERATIONS, CRAIG DENNY, WAS NOTIFIED AT 2:58 AM ABOUT A TANK CAR, RCRX 1111, HAVING A VAPOR CLOUD EMANATING FROM THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE. HE CONTACTED EAGLE CONSTRUCTION, A RAILROAD CONTRACTOR TO RESPOND AND INSPECT THE TANK CAR. THE LOUISIANA STATE POLICE WERE ALSO NOTIFIED AND ASSIGNED INCIDENT #0104554 TO THE INCIDENT. THE VENT LINE WAS REMOVED TO DETERMINE OUTAGE, AS IT WAS THOUGHT THE CAR WAS OVERLOADED. INSPECTION REVEALED THAT THE TANK CAR WAS NOT OVERLOADED. THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE WAS ALSO INSPECTED FOR DAMAGED OR MALFUNCTION AND NONE WERE OBSERVED. IT WAS FINALLY DETERMINED THAT DUE TO THE JOLT AS A RESULT OF HUMPING OPERATIONS, THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE OPERATED NORMALLY, AND ONCE PRESSURE WAS RELIEVED, THE VALVE CLOSED AS DESIGNED. THE TANK CAR WAS RELEASED TO DESTINATION.

column168: MIKE JOHNSON, MANAGER OF ENVIRONMENTAL FIELD OPERATIONS, WAS ADVISED BY THE YARDMASTER THAT TANK CAR GATX 43498, LOCATED ON THE WEST END OF TRACK 314 IN THE WEST  COLTON YARD. WAS REPORTED LEAKING.  INSPECTION REVEALED THAT THE LEAKING PROBLEM WAS CAUSED BY TWO LOOSE PACKING GLAND NUTS ON THE BOTTOM OUTLET HANDLE.  MGR JOHNSON TIGHTENING THE NUTS AND THE LEAK STOPPED.  THE SPILLED PRODUCTS WAS NEUTRALIZED AND THE TANK CAR RELEASED FOR TRANSPORTATION.

column168: ON THE ABOVE DATE RMCC CONTACTED CTS MGR. M. KELLY AND ADVISED THAT THE ABOVE TANK CAR HAD BEEN PLACED IN INTERCHANGE WITH THE DG&E RAILROAD AND THAT DURING THEIR INSPECTION OF THE CAR THEY OBSERVED THE ABOVE CAR LEAKING AT THE TOP NEAR THE SAFETY VENT.  THE CAR WAS INSPECTED AND IT WAS FOUND THAT THE FRANGIBLE DISK HAD BURST ALLOWING A SMALL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT TO SPILL OUT ONTO THE TOP OF THE CAR.  THE DISK WAS REPLACED WITH LIKE KIND AND THE CAR WAS RELEASED TO CONTINUE ONTO ITS DESTINATION.  THE SHIPPER AND CHEMTREC WERE NOTIFIED.

UNION PACIFIC RAILROAD'S CORRIDOR MANAGER REPORTED HE WAS CONTACTED BY JOHN FISHER, KIND AND KNOX GELLATIN- 712-943-5519, IN REGARD TO A TANK CAR OF HYDROCHLORIC ACID THAT HAD BEEN LEAKING ON THEIR PROPERTY.  MR. FISHER ADVISED THE LEAK HAD BEEN STOPPED BY PLUGGING THE LEAKING WELD AND REQUESTED UP RESPOND TO MOVE THE TANKCAR TO A SAFE LOCATION SO THE MATERIAL COULD BE TRANSLOADED.  MARK REIMERS, REGIONAL MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY CONSULTED WITH MR. FISHER AND WAS INFORMED THAT A TRANSFER HAD BEEN ATTEMPTED AT THE CURRENT LOCATION OF THE TANKCAR, BUT WAS UNSUCCESSFUL.  MR FISHER STATED THE TANKCAR HAD A PIN HOLE LEAK AT THE TOP OF THE TANKCAR AND HAD RELEASED APPROXIMATELY TWENTY TO THIRTY GALLONS OF PRODUCT.  MR. FISHER STATED THE RELEASED MATERIAL HAD BEEN CONTAINED AND THE LEAK WAS STOPPED.  MR. FISHER REPORTED  ENVIROTECH, CONTRACTOR, WAS ON SCENE ASSISTING WITH THE CLEAN UP.
KENNETH SIMPSON, MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY FOUND TANK CAR CELX 29038 LEAKING AT THE SAMPLE VALVE.  MANAGER SIMPSON CLOSED THE VALVE AND TIGHTENED THE PLUG 1/4 TURN.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Inadequate Blocking and Bracing
column168: SPECIAL AGENT HAZMAT DAVID SACHS WAS ADVISED OF A LEAKING CONTAINER IN THE PARR BLVD INTERMODAL FACILITY.  HE RESPOND FROM PORTOLA CA AND ARRIVED AT 1310 HOURS. ROBERT PELHAM FROM PSC WAS ALREADY ON SITE.  HE REPORTED THAT IT APPEARED THAT THE CONTAINER WAS NO LONGER LEAKING.  EMPU 293703 WAS STACKED ON TOP OF SPDU 682346 IN STACK CAR AOKA 055041.  THE ACID LEAKED FROM EMPU 293703 TO THE TOP AND SIDES OF SPDU 682703 AND TO THE SIDES OF THE AOKA 055041.  THE CONTAINERS WERE UNLOADED FROM THE STACK CAR AND PLACED ON PLASTIC SHEETING SO THAT THE CONTAINERS COULD BE DECONTAMINATED. EMPU 293703 WAS OPENED UP AND IT WAS FOUND THAT THERE WAS NO BRACING OR BLOCKING OF THE LOAD.  THE LOAD HAD SHIFTED FORWARD ON THE CONTAINER.  THE CHEMICALS WERE ON PALLETS WITH PLASTIC WRAPPING.  THE CHEMICALS BOTH IN BOXES AND IN PLASTIC BARRELS HAD SHIFTED OFF THE PALLETS AND TOWARD THE NOSE OF THE CONTAINER.  THE PHOSPHORIC ACID WAS LOADED AT THE NOSE OF THE CONTAINER IN 30 GALLON PLASTIC BARRELS.  THE FORCE OF THE LOAD SHIFT CAUSED ONE OF THE PLASTIC BARRELS TO COLLAPSE AND IT DEVELOPED A SMALL HOLE.  THIS CAUSED APPROXIMATELY ONE THIRD OF THE BARREL TO BE RELEASED.  BOTH THE CONTAINERS AND THE RAILCAR WERE DECONTAMINATED BY PSC.

TANK CAR PROX 14329 LEAKED APPROXIMATELY 10 GALLONS OF PRODUCT AS A RESULT OF A DEFECTIVE LIQUID EDUCTION LINE FLANGE GASKET.  INTERNAL PRESSURE WAS RELEASE TO MITIGATE THE ACTIVE LEAK.  MR. JOHN JACKSON, UPRR MGR. CHEM TRANSPORTATION SAFETY CONDUCTED SHIPPER VIA CHEMTREC.  SHIPPER UTILIZED CONTRACTOR TO REPAIR LIQUID EDUCTION LINE FLANGE GASKET AND DECONTAMINATE AFFECTED AREAS.  CAR WAS INSPECTED, PRESSURE TESTED, NO OTHER EXCEPTIONS NOTED AND RELEASED TO DESTINATION.

column168: THERE WERE NO INJURIES INVOLVED. SPILL REPORT-PHIL KNISLEY- 07/23/01 GE-WORTHINGTON,OHIO BY: JON CRAGG STL FORGOT TO CLOSE INTERNAL & EXTERNAL VALVES ON TRAILER BEFORE LOADING. DRIVER WAS SENT TO A CONTROL SHED TO WAIT TO BE LOADED. GE EMPLOYEE, KEVIN LAFT,WAS THE LOADER OF THIS PRODUCT. AFTER LOADING BEGAN, KEVIN WENT INSIDE OF GE PLANT TO DO SOMEOTHER TYPE OF WORK. KEVIN RETURNED TO STL UNIT AND SAW CLOUD OF SMOKE ABOVE LOADING FACILITY. KEVIN IMMEDIATELY RAN TO CONTROL VALVE AND STOPPED LOADING PROCEDURE. KEVIN THEN WENT TO REAR OF STL UNIT AND CLOSED EXTERNAL VALVE. GE CALLED WORTHINGTON FIRE DEPT. TO RESPOND TO SCENE BECAUSE OF CLOUD OF SMOKE ABOVE UNIT AND DRIFTING ACROSS HUNTLEY ROAD. FIRE DEPT. BLOCKED OFF THIS ROAD TO PREVENT CARS FROM TRAVELING THROUGH SMOKE. WORTHINGTON FIRE DEPT. DECIDED THIS WAS A CLASS I SPILL AND CALLED FOR BACKUP UNITS. SIX OTHER FIRE DEPARTMENTS RESPONDED TO SCENE. ALL FIRE DEPTS. ACTUALLY DID NOT HELP IN CLEANUP OF MATERIAL AND WERE RELEASED FORM SPILL SITE AFTER APPROX. ONE HOUR. GE EMPLOYEES HANDLED CLEANUP OF SPILL. MAJORITY OF SPILL WAS CONTAINED IN CONTAINMENT AREA. CONTAINMENT WALL HAD A CRACK IN IT AND SOME PRODUCT MIXED WITH WATER LEAKED ONTO SIDEWALK BUT WAS CONTAINED SO IT DIDN'T SPILL ONTO GRASSY AREA. GE HAS A SPRINKLER SYSTEM FOR WATER, WHICH WAS USED TO KNOCK DOWN CLOUD OF SMOKE THAT WAS RELEASED WHEN SPILLED PRODUCT CAME IN CONTACT WITH WATER IN CONTAINMENT AREA. I ARRIVED ON SCENE AT 0845 AND SPILLED PRODUCT HAS ALREADY BEEN FLUSHED DOWN INTO HOLDING TANK. BILL BUSCHE WAS GE EMPLOYEE IN CHARGE OF THIS INCIDENT. PHONE #614-325-0244. BILL BUSCHE IS A SAFETY SUPERVISOR FOR GE. SPILLED PRODUCT WAS DISPOSED OF BY GE AFTER TREATMENT THROUGH THEIR FILTERING SYSTEM AND RELEASED INTO CITY SEWAGE. 50 PEOPLE WERE EVACUATED FORM IMMEDIATE AREA AND PRODUCTION WAS SHUT DOWN FOR 1ST AND 2ND SHIFT.

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: OUR DRIVER STARTED HIS SHIFT AT APPROXIMATELY 01:30AM.  WHILE EN ROUTE TO DELIVER A LOAD OF GAS TO RACETRAC PETROLEUM, INC THE TRACTOR AND TRAILER OVERTURNED BREACHING SEVERAL COMPARTMENTS AND KILLING THE DRIVER. APPROXIMATELY 6000 GALLONS OF GASOLINE WAS SPILLED. GASTONIA FIRE DEPARTMENT HAZARDOUS MATERIALS TEAM WAS FIRST TO ARRIVE AT THE SCENE FOR CLEAN UP. HEPACO INCORPORATED AT 2711  BURCH DRIVE. CHARLOTTE, NC 28269  CONTINUED WITH THE CLEAN UP.  THE TRACTOR AND TRAILER WERE REMOVED FROM THE SCENE BY HAMPTONS WRECKER SERVICE, INC AND TAKEN TO THEIR FACILITY AT 620  NORTH ACADEMY STREET, LINCOLNTON, NC 28092.   DAVID A . BROWN, P.E., FROM THE WARREN GROUP, VISITED THE SCENE OF THE ACCIDENT ON 7/17/01 TO DETERMINE POSSIBLE CAUSES. THERE WAS NO EVIDENCE OF ANY OTHER VEHICLES INVOLVED IN THIS ACCIDENT.  ONE POSSIBILITY IS THAT THE DRIVER MAY HAVE FALLEN ASLEEP AT THE  WHEEL.  HIS DRIVER LOGS INDICATED THAT HE HAD NOT WORKED IN THE PREVIOUS FOUR DAYS .  LACK OF SKID MARKS INDICATES THAT SPEED WAS NOT A CONTRIBUTING FACTOR.  AS THERE WERE NO WITNESSES TO THE INCIDENT A DEFINITE CAUSE OF THE ACCIDENT CANNOT BE DETERMINED.
